{"title_page": "Vladislav Surkov", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2020}}\n{{Expand Ukrainian|\u0421\u0443\u0440\u043a\u043e\u0432 \u0412\u043b\u0430\u0434\u0438\u0441\u043b\u0430\u0432 \u042e\u0440\u0456\u0439\u043e\u0432\u0438\u0447|date=February 2020}}\n{{Eastern Slavic name|Yuryevich|Surkov}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| image        = Vladislav Surkov 7 May 2013.jpeg\n| imagesize    = 220px\n| caption      = Surkov in May 2012\n| order        = Assistant to the [[President of Russia|President of the Russian Federation]]\n| term_start   = 20 September 2013\n| term_end     = 18 February 2020\n| president1   = [[Vladimir Putin]]\n| office2      = [[Deputy Chairman of the Government of the Russian Federation|Deputy Prime Minister of Russia]] \u2014 Head of the Government Executive Office\n| term_start2  = 21 May 2012\n| term_end2    = 8 May 2013\n| primeminister2 = [[Dmitry Medvedev]]\n| predecessor2 = [[Vyacheslav Volodin]]\n| successor2   = [[Sergey Prikhodko]]\n| office3      = [[Deputy Chairman of the Government of the Russian Federation|Deputy Prime Minister of Russia]] \n| term_start3  = 27 December 2011\n| term_end3    = 21 May 2012\n| primeminister3 = [[Vladimir Putin]]<br />[[Dmitry Medvedev]]\n| predecessor3 = \n| successor3   = \n| office4      = First Deputy Chief of Staff of the [[Presidential Administration of Russia]] \n| term_start4  = 15 May 2008\n| term_end4    = 27 December 2011\n| president4   = [[Dmitry Medvedev]]\n| office5      = Deputy Chief of Staff of the [[Presidential Administration of Russia]] \n| term_start5  = 3 August 1999\n| term_end5    = 12 May 2008\n| president5   = [[Boris Yeltsin]]<br/ >[[Vladimir Putin]]\n| birth_name   = Aslambek Andarbekovich Dudayev\n| birth_date   = {{Birth date and age|1962|9|21|df=y}}<br />{{Birth date and age|1964|9|21|df=y}} (sources differ)\n| birth_place  = [[Soviet Union]]{{efn|Surkov's official biography claims his birth place as Solntsevo, [[Lipetsk Oblast]], [[Russian Soviet Federative Socialist Republic|Russian SFSR]], however other sources claim his birth place as [[Shali, Chechen Republic|Shali]], [[Checheno-Ingush Autonomous Soviet Socialist Republic|Checheno-Ingush-ASSR]].}}\n| party        = [[United Russia]]\n| spouse       = {{marriage|Yulia Vishnevskaya|1987|1996|end=div}}<br />{{marriage|Natalya Dubovitskaya<br>|1998}}\n| children     = 4\n| alma_mater   = [[International University in Moscow]]\n| profession   = \n| signature    = Signature of Vladislav Surkov.png\n}}\n\n'''Vladislav Yuryevich Surkov''' ({{lang-ru|\u0412\u043b\u0430\u0434\u0438\u0441\u043b\u0430\u0301\u0432 \u042e\u0301\u0440\u044c\u0435\u0432\u0438\u0447 \u0421\u0443\u0440\u043a\u043e\u0301\u0432}}, [[n\u00e9]] '''Aslambek Andarbekovich Dudayev''', \u0410\u0441\u043b\u0430\u043c\u0431\u0435\u0301\u043a \u0410\u043d\u0434\u0430\u0440\u0431\u0435\u043a\u043e\u0432\u0438\u0447 \u0414\u0443\u0434\u0430\u0301\u0435\u0432; born 21 September 1962 or 1964, sources differ)<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.gazeta.ru/politics/elections2007/parts/1477554.shtml|title=\u0411\u0435\u0441\u043f\u0430\u0440\u0442\u0438\u0439\u043d\u044b\u0439 \u0438\u0434\u0435\u043e\u043b\u043e\u0433 \u0412\u043b\u0430\u0434\u0438\u0441\u043b\u0430\u0432 \u0421\u0443\u0440\u043a\u043e\u0432|date=16 May 2007|work=[[Gazeta.ru]]|accessdate=1 April 2009}}{{dead link|date=April 2020}}</ref> is a Russian businessman and politician. He was First Deputy Chief of the [[Presidential Administration of Russia|Russian Presidential Administration]] from 1999 to 2011, during which time he was often viewed as the main ideologist of the [[Kremlin]] who proposed and implemented the concept of [[sovereign democracy]] in Russia. From December 2011 until May 2013, Surkov served as the Russian Federation's Deputy Prime Minister.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://en.kremlin.ru/events/president/news/14156|title=Vladislav Surkov has been appointed Deputy Prime Minister|website=President of&nbsp;Russia}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | title = Russian President Accepts Resignation Of Deputy PM Surkov | url = http://www.rferl.org/content/russia-deputy-pm-surkov-quits/24980174.html | work = [[Radio Free Europe]] |  date = 8 May 2013}}</ref> After his resignation, Surkov returned to the Presidential Executive Office and became a personal adviser of [[Vladimir Putin]] on relationships with [[Abkhazia]], [[South Ossetia]] and [[Ukraine]].<ref name=\"forbes.ua\">{{cite web | last = \u0412\u0438\u043d\u043e\u043a\u0443\u0440\u043e\u0432\u0430 | first = \u0415\u043a\u0430\u0442\u0435\u0440\u0438\u043d\u0430 | title = \u0427\u0435\u043c \u0412\u043b\u0430\u0434\u0438\u0441\u043b\u0430\u0432 \u0421\u0443\u0440\u043a\u043e\u0432 \u0437\u0430\u0439\u043c\u0435\u0442\u0441\u044f \u0432 \u0423\u043a\u0440\u0430\u0438\u043d\u0435 | url = http://forbes.ua/nation/1358330-chem-vladislav-surkov-zajmetsya-v-ukraine | work = [[Forbes|Forbes.ua]] | date = 20 September 2013}}</ref> He was fired from this duty by presidential order in February 2020.<ref name=\":8\">{{Cite web|url=https://meduza.io/en/news/2020/02/18/putin-officially-fires-top-political-curator-vladislav-surkov|title=Putin officially fires top political aide Vladislav Surkov|website=meduza.io|access-date=18 February 2020}}</ref>\n\nSurkov is perceived by many to be a [[\u00c9minence grise|key figure with much power and influence]] in the administration of Vladimir Putin.<ref name=\"RE01\" /><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.ibtimes.co.uk/vladislav-surkov-who-vladimir-putins-grey-cardinal-1588913|title=Vladislav Surkov: Who is Vladimir Putin's 'grey cardinal'?|last=Thomas|first=Matt|date=29 October 2016|newspaper=International Business Times UK|access-date=21 November 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"LOB01\" /> According to ''[[The Moscow Times]]'', this perception is not dependent on the official title Surkov might hold at any one time in the Putin government.<ref name=\":5\">{{Cite news|url=https://themoscowtimes.com/articles/same-old-kremlin-same-old-surkov-28364|title=Same Old Kremlin, Same Old Surkov|last=Ryzhkov|first=Vladimir|date=7 October 2013|work=[[The Moscow Times]]|quote=Surkov played the decisive role in raising Kadyrov to his current post. For his part, Kadyrov refers to Surkov as his \"sworn brother\" and even has a portrait of Surkov hanging in his office in [[Grozny]].\"  and  \"...a person's formal job title in Russia never matches the actual authority they wield.|access-date=20 November 2016|via=}}</ref> [[BBC]] [[documentary film]]maker [[Adam Curtis]] credits Surkov's blend of [[Theatre|theater]] and [[politics]] with keeping Putin, [[Tandemocracy (Russia)|and Putin's chosen successors]], in power since 2000.<ref name=\":6\" />\n\nJournalists in Russia and abroad have speculated that Surkov writes under the [[pseudonym]] '''Nathan Dubovitsky''', although [[Moscow Kremlin|the Kremlin]] denies it.<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.vedomosti.ru/politics/articles/2009/08/13/vladislav-surkov-stal-pisatelem|title=\u0412\u043b\u0430\u0434\u0438\u0441\u043b\u0430\u0432 \u0421\u0443\u0440\u043a\u043e\u0432 \u0441\u0442\u0430\u043b \u043f\u0438\u0441\u0430\u0442\u0435\u043b\u0435\u043c?|last=Glikin|first=Maksim|date=13 August 2009|work=[[Vedomosti]]|last2=Kholmogorova|first2=Vera|trans-title=Has Vladislav Surkov become a writer?|quote=Published novel ''Close to Zero'' was probably written by Vladislav Surkov. (\u0418\u0437\u0434\u0430\u043d \u0440\u043e\u043c\u0430\u043d \u00ab\u041e\u043a\u043e\u043b\u043e\u043d\u043e\u043b\u044f\u00bb, \u043d\u0430\u043f\u0438\u0441\u0430\u043d\u043d\u044b\u0439 \u0441\u043a\u043e\u0440\u0435\u0435 \u0432\u0441\u0435\u0433\u043e \u0412\u043b\u0430\u0434\u0438\u0441\u043b\u0430\u0432\u043e\u043c \u0421\u0443\u0440\u043a\u043e\u0432\u044b\u043c.)|access-date=20 November 2016|via=}}</ref><ref name=\"Storey\" /><ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.lrb.co.uk/blog/2014/03/28/peter-pomerantsev/non-linear-war/|title=Peter Pomerantsev: Non-Linear War|website=LRB blog|access-date=20 November 2016}}</ref><ref name=\":2\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/europe/did-kremlin-political-chief-really-write-murky-gangster-novel-1771881.html|title=Did Kremlin political chief really write murky gangster novel?|date=14 August 2009|newspaper=The Independent|language=en-GB|access-date=20 November 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Early years==\nAccording to Surkov's official biography, he was born 21 September 1964 in Solntsevo, [[Lipetsk Oblast]], [[Russian Soviet Federative Socialist Republic|Russian SFSR]].<ref name=bio>{{cite web|title=\u0421\u0443\u0440\u043a\u043e\u0432 \u0412\u043b\u0430\u0434\u0438\u0441\u043b\u0430\u0432 \u042e\u0440\u044c\u0435\u0432\u0438\u0447 |url=http://www.government.ru/persons/171/ |work=government.ru |language=Russian |date=12 March 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120312213526/http://www.government.ru/persons/171/ |archivedate=12 March 2012 }}</ref><ref name=\"kremlinbio\">{{cite web | title = Surkov, Vladislav | url = http://en.kremlin.ru/catalog/persons/2/biography | work = kremlin.ru | accessdate = 12 October 2015}}</ref> As per other statements, he was born in 1962 in [[Shali, Chechen Republic|Shali]], [[Checheno-Ingush Autonomous Soviet Socialist Republic|Checheno-Ingush ASSR]].<ref name=\"scandaly\">{{cite web|last1=\u041c\u0430\u0440\u0438\u043d\u0438\u043d |first1=\u041c\u0430\u043a\u0441\u0438\u043c |last2=\u041a\u043e\u0441\u0430\u0440\u0435\u0432\u0430 |first2=\u0418\u0440\u0438\u043d\u0430 |url=http://scandaly.ru/news/news3611.html |title=\u0427\u0415\u0427\u0415\u041d\u0421\u041a\u041e\u0415 \u0414\u0415\u0422\u0421\u0422\u0412\u041e \u0421\u0423\u0420\u041a\u041e\u0412\u0410 |work=scandaly.ru |language=Russian |date=13 July 2005 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080518033227/http://scandaly.ru/news/news3611.html |archivedate=18 May 2008 }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|url=https://www.refworld.org/docid/5194b06b4.html|title=Intrigue and Gossip Overwhelm Moscow after Surkov's Downfall|publisher=[[Jamestown Foundation]]|journal=Eurasia Daily Monitor|volume=10|issue=88|last=Felgenhauer|first=Pavel|date=9 May 2013|access-date=11 April 2020}}</ref> His name when he was born is reported to be '''Aslambek Dudayev'''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://medium.com/@wmilam/the-theater-director-who-is-vladislav-surkov-9dd8a15e0efb|title=Who is Vladislav Surkov?|website=[[Medium (website)|Medium]]|last=Milam|first=Whitney|date=14 July 2018|access-date=25 July 2019}}</ref> His parents, the ethnic [[History of the Jews in Russia|Jewish Russian]] Zinaida Antonovna Surkova (born 1935) and the ethnic [[Chechens|Chechen]] Yuriy (\"Andarbek\") Danil'bekovich Dudayev (born 1942), were school teachers in [[Shalinsky District, Chechen Republic|Duba-yurt]], Checheno-Ingush ASSR.<ref name=\"scandaly\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=https://worldview.stratfor.com/article/kremlin-wars-special-series-part-4-surkov-presses-home|title=The Kremlin Wars (Special Series), Part 4: Surkov Presses Home|website=[[Stratfor]]|date=27 October 2009|url-access=subscription|access-date=11 April 2020}}</ref> Following the separation of his parents, his mother moved to [[Lipetsk]] and he was baptized into [[Eastern Orthodox Christianity]].<ref name=\"mtimes\">{{cite news| title = 5 Facts About Vladislav Surkov | url = http://www.themoscowtimes.com/news/article/5-facts-about-vladislav-surkov/479739.html | work = [[The Moscow Times]] | date = 13 May 2013}}</ref> In an interview published in June 2005 in the German magazine ''[[Der Spiegel]]'', Surkov stated that his father was ethnic Chechen and that he spent the first five years of his life in Chechnya,<ref>[http://www.spiegel.de/spiegel/0,1518,361084,00.html 'Der Westen muss uns nicht lieben']. Uwe Von Klu\u00dfmann. Walter Mayr. [[Der Spiegel]]. 20 June 2005. Quote: \"Ich selbst habe die ersten f\u00fcnf Jahre meines Lebens in Tschetschenien zugebracht.\"</ref> in Duba-yurt and [[Grozny]].<ref name=LOB01>[[Peter Pomerantsev|Pomerantsev, Peter]]. [http://www.lrb.co.uk/v33/n20/peter-pomerantsev/putins-rasputin 'Putin's Rasputin']. ''[[London Review of Books]]''. 33 (20). 20 October 2011. pp. 3\u20136.</ref><ref>[http://www.inosmi.ru/translation/220396.html '\u0412\u043b\u0430\u0434\u0438\u0441\u043b\u0430\u0432 \u0421\u0443\u0440\u043a\u043e\u0432: \"\u0417\u0430\u043f\u0430\u0434 \u043d\u0435 \u043e\u0431\u044f\u0437\u0430\u043d \u043d\u0430\u0441 \u043b\u044e\u0431\u0438\u0442\u044c\",'] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20050831170152/http://www.inosmi.ru/translation/220396.html |date=31 August 2005 }} in Inopressa Newsagency. 20 June 2005.</ref> Surkov is reportedly a relative of [[Dzhokhar Dudayev]], the first [[President of the Chechen Republic of Ichkeria]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.themoscowtimes.com/2013/09/22/surkov-makes-kremlin-comeback-a27890|title=Surkov Makes Kremlin Comeback|newspaper=The Moscow Times|date=22 September 2013|access-date=10 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nFrom 1982 to 1983, Surkov attended [[National University of Science and Technology MISiS (Russia)|MISiS]], but did not graduate from it. From 1983 to 1985, Surkov served in a Soviet artillery regiment in [[Hungary]], according to his official biography.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.opendemocracy.net/od-russia/richard-sakwa/surkov-dark-prince-of-kremlin|title=Surkov: dark prince of the Kremlin|last=Sakwa|first=Richard|date=7 April 2011|website=[[openDemocracy]]|publisher=|access-date=20 November 2016}}</ref> However, former [[Defence Minister]] [[Sergei Ivanov]] stated in a 2006 TV interview that Surkov served in the [[GRU|Main Intelligence Directorate of the General Staff]] (GRU) during the same time period.<ref name=\"lenta.ru\">[http://lenta.ru/lib/14159273/full.htm ''\u0421\u0443\u0440\u043a\u043e\u0432, \u0412\u043b\u0430\u0434\u0438\u0441\u043b\u0430\u0432'']. lenta.ru</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://perebezhchik.ru/person/surkov-vladislav--yurevich/|title=\u0421\u0443\u0440\u043a\u043e\u0432 \u0412\u043b\u0430\u0434\u0438\u0441\u043b\u0430\u0432 \u042e\u0440\u044c\u0435\u0432\u0438\u0447 \u2013 \u0434\u043e\u0441\u044c\u0435, \u0432\u0441\u0435 \u043d\u043e\u0432\u043e\u0441\u0442\u0438|last=|first=|date=|work=|newspaper=\u041f\u0435\u0440\u0435\u0431\u0435\u0436\u0447\u0438\u043a|trans-title=Vladislav, Surkov Yurevich \u2013 dossier and news|quote=According to one information source, he served in the artillery of the Southern Group of Forces in Hungary. According to another, he served in the special forces of the Main Intelligence Directorate (GRU). (\u041f\u043e \u043e\u0434\u043d\u043e\u0439 \u0438\u043d\u0444\u043e\u0440\u043c\u0430\u0446\u0438\u0438, \u0441\u043b\u0443\u0436\u0431\u0443 \u043e\u043d \u043f\u0440\u043e\u0445\u043e\u0434\u0438\u043b \u0432 \u0430\u0440\u0442\u0438\u043b\u043b\u0435\u0440\u0438\u0439\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0439 \u0447\u0430\u0441\u0442\u0438 \u042e\u0436\u043d\u043e\u0439 \u0433\u0440\u0443\u043f\u043f\u044b \u0432\u043e\u0439\u0441\u043a \u0432 \u0412\u0435\u043d\u0433\u0440\u0438\u0438. \u041f\u043e \u0434\u0440\u0443\u0433\u043e\u0439 \u2013 \u0432 \u0441\u043f\u0435\u0446\u043d\u0430\u0437\u0435 \u0413\u043b\u0430\u0432\u043d\u043e\u0433\u043e \u0440\u0430\u0437\u0432\u0435\u0434\u044b\u0432\u0430\u0442\u0435\u043b\u044c\u043d\u043e\u0433\u043e \u0443\u043f\u0440\u0430\u0432\u043b\u0435\u043d\u0438\u044f (\u0413\u0420\u0423).)|access-date=20 November 2016|via=}}</ref>\n\nAfter his military training, Surkov was accepted{{when|date=March 2015}} to [[Moscow Institute of Culture]] for a five-year program in theater direction, but spent only three years there.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.themoscowtimes.com/people/article/vladislav_surkov/433802.html|title=Vladislav Surkov Biography|date=25 March 2011|publisher=[[The Moscow Times]]|access-date=20 November 2016|url-status=bot: unknown|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140902152411/http://www.themoscowtimes.com/people/article/vladislav_surkov/433802.html|archivedate=2 September 2014|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Surkov graduated from [[Moscow International University]] with a master's degree in economics in the late 1990s.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n==Business career (1988\u20131998)==\nIn the late 1980s, when the government lifted the ban against private businesses, Surkov started out in business. In 1987, he became head of the advertising department of [[Mikhail Khodorkovsky]]'s businesses. From 1991 to April 1996, he held key managerial positions in advertising and PR departments of Khodorkovsky's [[Bank Menatep]]. From March 1996 to February 1997, he was at Rosprom, and since February 1997 with [[Mikhail Fridman]]'s [[Alfa-Bank]].<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nIn September 2004, Surkov was elected president of the board of directors of the oil products transportation company [[Transnefteproduct]], but was instructed by Russia's prime minister [[Mikhail Fradkov]] to give up the position in February 2006.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.kommersant.ru/doc/649226|title=\u0412\u043b\u0430\u0434\u0438\u0441\u043b\u0430\u0432 \u0421\u0443\u0440\u043a\u043e\u0432 \u043f\u043e\u043a\u0438\u043d\u0435\u0442 \"\u0422\u0440\u0430\u043d\u0441\u043d\u0435\u0444\u0442\u0435\u043f\u0440\u043e\u0434\u0443\u043a\u0442\"|last=|first=|date=13 February 2006|work=|newspaper=\u041a\u043e\u043c\u043c\u0435\u0440\u0441\u0430\u043d\u0442\u044a ([[Kommersant]])|issue=25|pages=13|language=Russian|trans-title=Vladislav Surkov leaves \"Transnefteprodukt\"|quote=By an order signed by Prime Minister [[Mikhail Fradkov]], the Board of Directors of \"Transnefteprodukt\", Deputy of the Presidential Executive Office Vladislav Surkov, resigns. (\u041f\u043e \u043f\u043e\u0434\u043f\u0438\u0441\u0430\u043d\u043d\u043e\u043c\u0443 \u043f\u0440\u0435\u043c\u044c\u0435\u0440\u043e\u043c \u041c\u0438\u0445\u0430\u0438\u043b\u043e\u043c \u0424\u0440\u0430\u0434\u043a\u043e\u0432\u044b\u043c \u0440\u0430\u0441\u043f\u043e\u0440\u044f\u0436\u0435\u043d\u0438\u044e, \u0441\u043e\u0432\u0435\u0442 \u0434\u0438\u0440\u0435\u043a\u0442\u043e\u0440\u043e\u0432 \u041e\u0410\u041e \"\u0422\u0440\u0430\u043d\u0441\u043d\u0435\u0444\u0442\u0435\u043f\u0440\u043e\u0434\u0443\u043a\u0442\" \u043f\u043e\u043a\u0438\u043d\u0435\u0442 \u0432\u043e\u0437\u0433\u043b\u0430\u0432\u043b\u044f\u0432\u0448\u0438\u0439 \u0435\u0433\u043e \u0437\u0430\u043c\u0435\u0441\u0442\u0438\u0442\u0435\u043b\u044c \u0440\u0443\u043a\u043e\u0432\u043e\u0434\u0438\u0442\u0435\u043b\u044f \u0430\u0434\u043c\u0438\u043d\u0438\u0441\u0442\u0440\u0430\u0446\u0438\u0438 \u043f\u0440\u0435\u0437\u0438\u0434\u0435\u043d\u0442\u0430 \u0420\u0424 \u0412\u043b\u0430\u0434\u0438\u0441\u043b\u0430\u0432 \u0421\u0443\u0440\u043a\u043e\u0432.)|access-date=20 November 2016|via=}}</ref>\n\n==Political career (1999\u2013)==\n\n===Deputy Chief of the Russian Presidential Administration 1999\u20132011===\nAfter a brief career as a director for public relations on the Russian television [[Channel One (Russia)|ORT]] channel from 1998 to 1999, Surkov was appointed Deputy Chief of [[Russian presidential administration|Staff]] of the President of the Russian Federation in 1999.<ref name=Storey>{{cite web | last = Storey | first = Peter | title = Vladislav Surkov: The (Gray) Cardinal of the Kremlin | url = http://ciceromagazine.com/features/the-gray-cardinal-of-the-kremlin/ | work = [[Cicero (magazine)|Cicero]] | date = 17 June 2015 | accessdate = 9 November 2015}}</ref>\n\nDuring the beginning of his time in this role, Surkov's main appearances in public and in international media were as a [[public relations]] mouthpiece of the Kremlin. In August 2000, he confirmed that [[Gazprom]] would buy [[Vladimir Gusinsky]]'s [[Gazprom-Media|Media-Most]], which at the time owned the only independent, nationwide Russian television channel, [[NTV (Russia)|NTV]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/image/120736880/?terms=Vladislav%2BSurkov|title=Kremlin closing in on media network|last=|first=|date=4 August 2008|work=[[The Sydney Morning Herald]]|access-date=|via=Newspapers.com}}</ref> In September 2002, he stated on behalf of the Kremlin that they had decided not to return the statue of [[KGB]] founder [[Felix Dzerzhinsky]] that had been torn down during [[Dissolution of the Soviet Union|the fall of the Soviet Union]] in 1991.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/image/202201676/?terms=Vladislav%2BSurkov|title=Return of statue opposed|last=Gutterman|first=Steve|date=20 September 2002|work=[[Statesman Journal]] via [[Associated Press]]|page=7A|access-date=|via=Newspapers.com}}</ref> After the [[2003 Russian legislative election|2003 Russian Duma elections]], when the president's [[United Russia|United Russia party]] got the most [[State Duma|seats]] at 37.6%, Surkov delivered the Kremlin's enthusiastic response, saying \"We are living in a new Russia now.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://articles.latimes.com/2003/dec/09/world/fg-putin9|title=The Victor Extends an Olive Branch|last=Holley|first=David|date=9 December 2003|newspaper=Los Angeles Times|language=en-US|issn=0458-3035|access-date=23 November 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2004, he was additionally appointed as aide to the president.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://polit.ru/news/2015/09/21/surkov/|title=\u041c\u0435\u043c\u043e\u0440\u0438\u044f. \u0412\u043b\u0430\u0434\u0438\u0441\u043b\u0430\u0432 \u0421\u0443\u0440\u043a\u043e\u0432|last=|first=|date=21 September 2015|website= polit.ru|publisher=|language=Russian|trans-title=Vladislav Surkov fact sheet|access-date=20 November 2016}}</ref>\n\nSince 2006, Surkov has advocated a political doctrine he has called [[sovereign democracy]], to counter democracy promotion conducted by the USA and European states.<ref>[http://www.cdi.org/russia/johnson/2006-212-37.cfm] title? cdi.org. 2006.</ref> Judged by some Western media as controversial, this view has not generally been shared by Russian media and the Russian political elite.<ref name=\"roundtable\">[http://www.izvestia.ru/politic/article3096139/?print On Wednesday Political Elite Agreed to Speak Common Language]. \u00abIzvestia\u00bb. 31 August 2006.</ref> Surkov sees this concept as a national version of the common political language that will be used when Russia talks to the outside world.<ref name=\"roundtable\"/> As the most influential ideologist of \"sovereign democracy\", Surkov gave two programmatic speeches in 2006: \"Sovereignty is a Political Synonym of Competitiveness\" in February<ref>[http://www.edinros.ru/news.html?id=111148 Sovereignty is a Political Synonym of Competitiveness] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20061208020210/http://www.edinros.ru/news.html?id=111148 |date=8 December 2006 }}. Vladislav Surkov, public appearance. 7 February 2006.</ref> and \"Our Russian Model of Democracy is Titled Sovereign Democracy\" in June 2006.<ref>[http://www.edinros.ru/news.html?id=114108 Our Russian Model of Democracy is Titled \u00abSovereign Democracy\u00bb] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20061105125847/http://www.edinros.ru/news.html?id=114108 |date=5 November 2006 }}. Vladislav Surkov, briefing. 28 June 2006. edinros.ru.</ref>\n[[File:Vladislav Surkov in 2010.jpeg|thumb|left|Vladislav Surkov in April 2010]]\n\nOn 8 February 2007, [[Moscow State University]] marked the 125th anniversary of U.S. President [[Franklin D. Roosevelt]]'s birth with a high-level conference \"Lessons of the [[New Deal]] for Modern Russia and the World\" attended, among others, by Surkov and [[Gleb Pavlovsky]]. Surkov drew an explicit parallel between Roosevelt and Russian president Putin, praising the legacy of Roosevelt's New Deal, and between the US of the 1930s and present-day Russia. Pavlovsky called on Putin to follow Roosevelt in staying for a third presidential term.<ref>[http://www.kommersant.com/p741228/Putin_Roosevelt_Third_Term/ \u0412\u043b\u0430\u0434\u0438\u043c\u0438\u0440 \u0412\u043b\u0430\u0434\u0438\u043c\u0438\u0440\u043e\u0432\u0438\u0447 \u0420\u0443\u0437\u0432\u0435\u043b\u044c\u0442/ Putin Asked to Follow FDR's Example]. ''[[Kommersant]]''. 9 February 2007.</ref><ref>[http://www.mosnews.com/news/2007/02/09/putinroosvelt.shtml Kremlin Official Compares Putin to Franklin D. Roosevelt]. [[Moscow News]]. 9 February 2007.</ref><ref>[http://en.rian.ru/russia/20070208/60427066.html Roosevelt Russia's ideological ally \u2013 Putin aide]. [[RIA Novosti]]. 8 February 2007.</ref>\n\nAccording to ''[[The Moscow Times]]'', Surkov exerted his influence to have [[Ramzan Kadyrov]] appointed as acting [[Head of the Chechen Republic]] on 15 February 2007.<ref name=\":5\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.forbes.ru/sobytiya-photogallery/vlast/238819-put-surkova-ot-ohrannika-do-vitse-premera/photo/11|title=\u0421\u0443\u0440\u043a\u043e\u0432 \u0438 \u041a\u0430\u0434\u044b\u0440\u043e\u0432|last=13 May 2013|first=|date=|website=www.forbes.ru|publisher=[[Forbes]] Russia|trans-title=Surkov and Kadyrov|access-date=20 November 2016}}</ref> Since this appointment, Kadyrov has gone on to serve two terms in office and has been accused of numerous humans rights abuses.<ref>See [[Ramzan Kadyrov#Accusations of human rights abuses|Ramzan Kadyrov \u00a7\u00a7 Accusations of human rights abuses]]</ref>\n\nIn October 2009, Surkov warned that opening and modernization of Russia's political system, a need repeatedly stressed by President [[Dmitry Medvedev]], could result in more instability, which \"could rip Russia apart\".<ref>Sirke M\u00e4kinen, \"Surkovian narrative on the future of Russia: making Russia a world leader.\" ''Journal of Communist Studies and Transition Politics'' 27#2 (2011): 143\u2013165.</ref>\n\nIn September 2011, [[Mikhail Prokhorov]] quit the [[Party of Growth|Right Cause party]], which he had led for five months. He condemned the party as a puppet of the Kremlin and named Surkov the \"main puppet master of the political process\" ({{Lang-ru|\u0433\u043b\u0430\u0432\u043d\u044b\u043c \u043a\u0443\u043a\u043b\u043e\u0432\u043e\u0434\u043e\u043c \u043f\u043e\u043b\u0438\u0442\u0438\u0447\u0435\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0433\u043e \u043f\u0440\u043e\u0446\u0435\u0441\u0441\u0430|link=no}}), according to a report in Russian-language magazine ''[[Korrespondent]]'' picked up by ''The New York Times''.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://korrespondent.net/russia/1261740-prohorov-nazval-glavnogo-kuklovoda-politicheskogo-processa-v-rossii|title=\u041f\u0440\u043e\u0445\u043e\u0440\u043e\u0432 \u043d\u0430\u0437\u0432\u0430\u043b  \u0433\u043b\u0430\u0432\u043d\u043e\u0433\u043e \u043a\u0443\u043a\u043b\u043e\u0432\u043e\u0434\u0430 \u043f\u043e\u043b\u0438\u0442\u0438\u0447\u0435\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0433\u043e \u043f\u0440\u043e\u0446\u0435\u0441\u0441\u0430 \u0432 \u0420\u043e\u0441\u0441\u0438\u0438|last=|first=|date=15 September 2011|work=[[Korrespondent]]|language=Russian|access-date=20 November 2016|via=}}</ref><ref>Kramer, Andrew E., and Ellen Barry, [https://www.nytimes.com/2011/09/16/world/europe/amid-political-rancor-russian-party-leader-mikhail-prokhorov-quits.html?hp \"Amid Political Rancor, Russian Party Leader Quits\"]. ''The New York Times''. 15 September 2011. Retrieved 15 September 2011.</ref> Prokhorov had hoped that Surkov would be fired from the Kremlin, but the Kremlin stood behind Surkov and said he would not disappear from the political stage.<ref>Volkskrant. 16 September 2011.</ref> At that time, ''[[Reuters]]'' described Surkov in a profile as the Kremlin's 'shadowy chief political strategist', one of the most powerful men in the Kremlin and considered a close ally of then-Prime Minister Putin.<ref name=RE01/>\n\n===Deputy Prime Minister for Economic Modernisation 2011\u20132013===\nOn 28 December 2011, Medvedev reassigned Surkov to the role of \"Deputy Prime Minister for Economic Modernisation\" in a move interpreted by many to be fallout from the controversial [[2011 Russian legislative election|Russian parliamentary elections of 2011]].<ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/world/2011/dec/27/vladimir-putin-ejects-vladislav-surkov \"Putin ejects Kremlin 'puppet master' after protests\"]. Associated Press via ''The Guardian''. 27 December 2011.</ref> At that time, Surkov described his past career as follows:<ref>[http://rbth.ru/articles/2011/12/28/the_gray_cardinal_leaves_the_kremlin_14123.html The gray cardinal leaves the Kremlin]. ''Russia Beyond the Headlines''. 28 December 2011.</ref> \"I was among those who helped [[Boris Yeltsin]] to secure a peaceful transfer of power; among those who helped President Putin stabilize the political system; among those who helped President Medvedev liberalize it. All the teams were great.\"\n\n[[File:\u0412\u043b\u0430\u0434\u0438\u0441\u043b\u0430\u0432 \u0421\u0443\u0440\u043a\u043e\u0432 \u043d\u0430 V \u0441\u044a\u0435\u0437\u0434\u0435 \u041d\u0410\u0428\u0418\u0445.JPG|thumb|Surkov giving a speech during the Fifth Congress of the Nashi Youth Movement]]\nDuring this time, Surkov helped create some pro-government youth movements, including [[Nashi (youth movement)|Nashi]]. He met with their leaders and participants several times and gave them lectures on the political situation.<ref>[http://www.ncsj.org/AuxPages/030205RFERL_Putin.shtml] ncsj.org  {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070124171111/http://www.ncsj.org/AuxPages/030205RFERL_Putin.shtml|date=24 January 2007}}</ref><ref>Maya Atwal and Edwin Bacon. \"The youth movement Nashi: contentious politics, civil society, and party politics.\" ''East European Politics'' 28.3 (2012): 256\u2013266.</ref> Nashi has been compared by [[Edward Lucas (journalist)|Edward Lucas]] as the Putin government's version of the Soviet-era [[Komsomol]].<ref>{{cite book|url=|title=The new cold war: Putin's Russia and the threat to the West|last=Lucas|first=Edward|publisher=St. Martin's Press|year=2014|isbn=9781137472618|edition=3rd|location=New York|pages=102\u2013105|quote=|via=}}{{rp|page=102}}\n</ref>[[File:Sergey Ivanov, Vladislav Surkov and Arkady Dvorkovich 7 May 2013.jpeg|thumb|Surkov on his last day as Deputy Prime Minister in a meeting with [[Sergei Ivanov|Sergey Ivanov]] ([[Kremlin Chief of Staff|Chief of Presidential Staff]]) and his ministerial colleague [[Arkady Dvorkovich]]]]\n\nSince Putin's return to the presidency in 2012, Surkov became marginalized as Putin \"pursued a path of open repression over the cunning manipulation favoured by Surkov\". As a Deputy Prime Minister, Surkov criticized the Kremlin's Investigative Committee, which led investigations into opposition leaders, rather than the general prosecutor's office. The Committee stated he offered to resign on 7 May 2013, whereas Surkov stated he offered to resign on 28 April 2013. Putin signed it on 8 May 2013.<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20130622185409/http://government.ru/persons/171/ ''\u0421\u0443\u0440\u043a\u043e\u0432 \u0412\u043b\u0430\u0434\u0438\u0441\u043b\u0430\u0432 \u042e\u0440\u044c\u0435\u0432\u0438\u0447'']. government.ru. 22 June 2013.</ref><ref>Miriam Elder: [https://www.theguardian.com/world/2013/may/08/vladimir-putin-cardinal-forced-government ''Vladimir Putin's former 'cardinal' forced out of government'']. The Guardian. 8 May 2013.</ref>\n\n===Personal advisor to Putin, 2013\u20132020===\n[[File:Normandy format talks 2016-10-19.jpg|thumb|The \"[[Normandy Format]]\" talks in 2016 where Surkov sits between [[Vladimir Putin]] and [[Frank-Walter Steinmeier]]]]\n[[File:Normandy format (2019-10-09) 03.jpg|thumb|The \"[[Normandy Format]]\" talks in 2019 where Surkov sits aside with [[Sergei Lavrov]]]]\nDuring Putin's first two terms as president, Surkov was regarded as the Kremlin's \"grey cardinal\", due to crafting Russia's system of \"sovereign democracy\" and directing its propaganda principally through control of state run television.<ref>Anna Nemtsova, Eli Lake: [http://www.thedailybeast.com/articles/2014/03/19/obama-targets-the-mastermind-behind-putin-s-power-play.html ''Is This the Mastermind Behind Russia's Crimea Grab?''] The Daily Beast. 19 March 2014</ref> On 20 September 2013, Vladimir Putin appointed Surkov as his Aide in the [[Presidential Administration of Russia|Presidential Executive Office]].<ref name=\"kremlinbio\" /> He also became Putin's personal adviser on relationships with [[Abkhazia]], [[South Ossetia]] and [[Ukraine]].<ref name=\"forbes.ua\"/><ref name=tass/>\n \nOn 17 March 2014, the day after the [[2014 Crimean referendum|Crimean status referendum]], Surkov became one of the first eleven persons who were placed under executive sanctions on the [[Office of Foreign Assets Control#Specially Designated Nationals List|Specially Designated Nationals List (SDN)]] by President [[Barack Obama]], freezing his assets in the US and banning him from entering the United States.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.businessinsider.com/crimea-vote-referendum-sanctions-obama-putin-2014-3|title=Obama Just Announced Sanctions Against 7 Russian 'Cronies'|journal=[[Business Insider]] |first=Brett| last=Logiurato| date=17 March 2014|accessdate=17 March 2014}}</ref><ref name=StateUkraineRussiaSanctions>{{cite web | title = Ukraine and Russia Sanctions | url = https://2009-2017.state.gov/e/eb/tfs/spi/ukrainerussia | publisher = United States State Department | accessdate = 4 March 2016}}</ref><ref name=FirstListWhiteHouse>{{cite web | title = Fact Sheet: Ukraine-Related Sanctions | url = https://www.whitehouse.gov/the-press-office/2014/03/17/fact-sheet-ukraine-related-sanctions | publisher = The White House: Office of the Press Secretary | date = 17 March 2014 | accessdate = 4 March 2016}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web | title = Executive Order \u2013 Blocking Property of Additional Persons Contributing to the Situation in Ukraine | url = http://www.whitehouse.gov/the-press-office/2014/03/20/executive-order-blocking-property-additional-persons-contributing-situat | publisher = The White House: Office of the Press Secretary | date = 20 March 2014 | accessdate = 4 March 2016}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|title=Treasury Sanctions Russian Officials, Members Of The Russian Leadership's Inner Circle, And An Entity For Involvement In The Situation In Ukraine |url=http://www.treasury.gov/press-center/press-releases/Pages/jl23331.aspx |publisher=United States Department of the Treasury}}</ref><ref name=TreasurySanctionsUkraineFirstList>{{cite web | title = Issuance of a new Ukraine-related Executive Order; Ukraine-related Designations  | url = https://www.treasury.gov/resource-center/sanctions/OFAC-Enforcement/Pages/20140317.aspx | publisher = United States Department of the Treasury | date = 17 March 2014 | accessdate = 4 March 2016}}</ref><ref name=TreasurySanctionsUkraineSecondList>{{cite web | title = Ukraine-related Designations | url = https://www.treasury.gov/resource-center/sanctions/OFAC-Enforcement/Pages/20140320_33.aspx | publisher = United States Department of the Treasury | date = 20 March 2014 | accessdate = 4 March 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | title = Specially Designated Nationals List (SDN) | url = http://www.treasury.gov/resource-center/sanctions/SDN-List/Pages/default.aspx | publisher = United States Department of the Treasury}}</ref><ref name=Sanctions>{{cite web | last = Shuklin | first = Peter | title = Putin's inner circle: who got in a new list of US sanctions | url = https://news.liga.net/articles/politics/1066761-blizhniy_krug_putina_kto_popal_v_novyy_spisok_sanktsiy_ssha.htm | publisher = liga.net | date = 21 March 2014 | accessdate = 20 February 2016 | url-status = dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20150207152258/http://news.liga.net/articles/politics/1066761-blizhniy_krug_putina_kto_popal_v_novyy_spisok_sanktsiy_ssha.htm | archivedate = 7 February 2015 | df = dmy-all }}</ref><ref name=Ukraine-EO13660>{{cite web | last = President of The United States | title = Ukraine EO13660 | url = https://www.treasury.gov/resource-center/sanctions/Programs/Documents/ukraine_eo.pdf | publisher = Federal Register | date = 10 March 2014 | accessdate = 4 March 2016}}</ref><ref name=Ukraine-EO13661>{{cite web | last = President of The United States | title = Ukraine EO13661 | url = https://www.treasury.gov/resource-center/sanctions/Programs/Documents/ukraine_eo2.pdf | publisher = Federal Register | date = 19 March 2014 | accessdate = 20 February 2016}}</ref>{{efn|The individuals on the first list of United States sanctions for individuals or entities involved in the Ukraine crisis are Sergey Aksyonov, Sergey Glazyev, Andrei Klishas, Vladimir Konstantinov, Valentina Matviyenko, Victor Medvedchuk, Yelena Mizulina, Dmitry Rogozin, Leonid Slutsky, Vladislav Surkov, and Victor Yakunovich.<ref name=FirstListWhiteHouse/><ref name=TreasurySanctionsUkraineFirstList/>}} Surkov responded to this by saying: \"The only things that interest me in the US are [[Tupac Shakur]], [[Allen Ginsberg]], and [[Jackson Pollock]]. I don\u2019t need a visa to access their work.\"<ref>[https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/europe/vladimir-putins-top-aide-vladislav-surkov-mocks-us-sanctions-the-only-thing-that-interests-me-about-9200170.html Vladimir Putin's top aide Vladislav Surkov mocks US sanctions]. ''[[The Independent]]''. 18 March 2014.</ref>\n\nOn 21 March 2014, the European Union (EU) placed Surkov on its [[List of individuals sanctioned during the Ukrainian crisis|sanction list]] barring him from entering the EU and freezing his assets in the EU.<ref name=\"EU-sanctions-21March\">{{cite web|url=http://eur-lex.europa.eu/legal-content/EN/TXT/?qid=1457224758727&uri=CELEX:32014R0284|title=Council Implementing Regulation (EU) No 284/2014 of 21 March 2014 implementing Regulation (EU) No 269/2014 concerning restrictive measures in respect of actions undermining or threatening the territorial integrity, sovereignty and independence of Ukraine (EUR-Lex \u2013 32014R0284 \u2013 EN)|work=EUR-Lex|date=21 March 2014}}</ref><ref name=BBC19Dec2014>{{cite web | title = Ukraine crisis: Russia and sanctions | url = https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-26672800 | publisher = BBC | date = 19 December 2014 | accessdate = 4 March 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2015, Ukrainian authorities accused Surkov of organizing snipers to kill protesters and police during the Ukrainian [[Euromaidan]] in January 2014.<ref>[https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-31548896 ''Ukraine accuses Russia over Maidan 2014 killings'']. bbc.com. 20 February 2015.</ref><ref>[http://www.pravda.com.ua/articles/2015/05/12/7067579/ ''Nemtsov Report: Putin. War'']. [[Ukrayinska Pravda]]. 12 May 2015.</ref><ref>[http://www.belsat.eu/en/articles/putins-aide-surkov-pulled-strings-snipers-shot-maidan-protesters-ukraines-sbu/ ''Putin's aide Surkov pulled the strings as snipers shot at Maidan protesters \u2013 Ukraine's SBU'']. belsat.eu. 20 February 2015. According to SBU director Nalyvaichenko, they have identified some of the shooters and \"as part of this case we have job titles, last names, copies of passports, dates of their entry and departure, their telephone providers and places of accommodation, [we know] how president Putin's adviser Surkov was coordinating their actions in Kyiv,\"</ref> This accusation was dismissed by the Russian government as \"absurd\".<ref name=tass>[http://tass.ru/en/russia/778994 ''Kiev's allegations that Surkov was behind Maidan developments in 2014 absurd \u2014 ForMin'']. [[Russian News Agency TASS|tass.ru]]. 20 February 2015.</ref>\n\nDespite being barred from entering the EU, Surkov visited Greece's [[Mount Athos]] as a part of Putin's delegation to the holy site in May 2016.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Shuster|first1=Simon|title=Exclusive: Putin Aide Vladislav Surkov Defied E.U. Sanctions to Make Pilgrimage to Greece|url=http://time.com/4476005/vladislav-surkov-putin-athos-greece-sanctions/|work=Time|date=2 September 2016}}</ref>\n\nOn 11 February 2019, Surkov published in the [[Nezavisimaya Gazeta]] article \u201cThe Long State of Putin\u201d, which describes the main points of the term \u201c[[Putinism]]\u201d proposed by him.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ng.ru/ideas/2019-02-11/5_7503_surkov.html|title=\u0412\u043b\u0430\u0434\u0438\u0441\u043b\u0430\u0432 \u0421\u0443\u0440\u043a\u043e\u0432: \u0414\u043e\u043b\u0433\u043e\u0435 \u0433\u043e\u0441\u0443\u0434\u0430\u0440\u0441\u0442\u0432\u043e \u041f\u0443\u0442\u0438\u043d\u0430|website=www.ng.ru|language=en|access-date=17 October 2019}}</ref> The article caused a stir in the media.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.helsinki.fi/en/news/society-economy/surkov-and-the-three-pillars-of-putinism|title=Surkov and the three pillars of Putinism|date=24 April 2019|website=University of Helsinki|language=en|access-date=17 October 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2019/mar/25/russian-meddling-vladimir-putin-vladislav-surkov|title=The confusion around Russian \u2018meddling\u2019 means they\u2019re already winning {{!}} Gabriel Gatehouse|last=Gatehouse|first=Gabriel|date=25 March 2019|work=The Guardian|access-date=17 October 2019|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/europe/putin-russia-kremlin-vladislav-surkov-grey-cardinal-moscow-a8773661.html|title=Putin advisor says 'Russia is playing with the West's minds'|date=12 February 2019|website=The Independent|language=en|access-date=17 October 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2020, Surkov was removed from his role of advisor.<ref name=\":8\" /> On 26 February 2020, he gave an interview to ''Aktualnyie kommentarii'' where he stated that he actually resigned from the post on his own initiative and the reasons were correctly disclosed by Russian journalists [[Vladimir Solovyov (journalist)|Vladimir Solovyev]]<ref>[https://www.kommersant.ru/doc/4233004 \u0414\u043c\u0438\u0442\u0440\u0438\u0439 \u041a\u043e\u0437\u0430\u043a \u0441\u043e\u0431\u0438\u0440\u0430\u0435\u0442\u0441\u044f \u0432 \u043d\u043e\u0432\u044b\u0439 \u043f\u043e\u0434\u0445\u043e\u0434 \u043d\u0430 \u0423\u043a\u0440\u0430\u0438\u043d\u0443]. ''Kommersant''.</ref> and [[Alexei Venediktov]].<ref name=actualcomment200226>{{cite web|url=http://actualcomment.ru/surkov-mne-interesno-deystvovat-protiv-realnosti-2002260855.html|title=Surkov: I am interested to act against the reality|website=Actualcomment.ru|last=Chesnakov|first=Aleksei|date=26 February 2020|language=ru|trans-title=\u0421\u0443\u0440\u043a\u043e\u0432: \u043c\u043d\u0435 \u0438\u043d\u0442\u0435\u0440\u0435\u0441\u043d\u043e \u0434\u0435\u0439\u0441\u0442\u0432\u043e\u0432\u0430\u0442\u044c \u043f\u0440\u043e\u0442\u0438\u0432 \u0440\u0435\u0430\u043b\u044c\u043d\u043e\u0441\u0442\u0438|quote=\u041f\u0440\u0438\u043d\u0443\u0436\u0434\u0435\u043d\u0438\u0435 \u0441\u0438\u043b\u043e\u0439 \u043a \u0431\u0440\u0430\u0442\u0441\u043a\u0438\u043c \u043e\u0442\u043d\u043e\u0448\u0435\u043d\u0438\u044f\u043c \u2014 \u0435\u0434\u0438\u043d\u0441\u0442\u0432\u0435\u043d\u043d\u044b\u0439 \u043c\u0435\u0442\u043e\u0434, \u0438\u0441\u0442\u043e\u0440\u0438\u0447\u0435\u0441\u043a\u0438 \u0434\u043e\u043a\u0430\u0437\u0430\u0432\u0448\u0438\u0439 \u044d\u0444\u0444\u0435\u043a\u0442\u0438\u0432\u043d\u043e\u0441\u0442\u044c \u043d\u0430 \u0443\u043a\u0440\u0430\u0438\u043d\u0441\u043a\u043e\u043c \u043d\u0430\u043f\u0440\u0430\u0432\u043b\u0435\u043d\u0438\u0438. \u041d\u0435 \u0434\u0443\u043c\u0430\u044e, \u0447\u0442\u043e \u0431\u0443\u0434\u0435\u0442 \u0438\u0437\u043e\u0431\u0440\u0435\u0442\u0435\u043d \u043a\u0430\u043a\u043e\u0439-\u0442\u043e \u0434\u0440\u0443\u0433\u043e\u0439.}}</ref> Surkov added that he was primarily involved with Donbass and Ukraine, but since the \"context\" has changed he decided to leave.<ref name=actualcomment200226/> He also explained that \"coercion to fraternal relations by force is the only method that has historically proven its effectiveness in the Ukrainian direction. I do not think that some other will be invented\".<ref name=actualcomment200226/>\n\n====Hacked emails====\n{{main|Surkov leaks}}\nIn October 2016, Ukrainian hacker group CyberHunta released over a gigabyte of emails and other documents alleged to belong to Surkov.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Windrem|first1=Robert|title=Payback? Russia gets hacked, revealing top Putin aide's secrets|url=http://www.nbcnews.com/storyline/ukraine-crisis/payback-russia-gets-hacked-revealing-putin-aide-s-secrets-n673956|work=NBC News|date=27 October 2016}}</ref> The 2,337 emails belonged to the inbox of Surkov's office email account, prm_surkova@gov.ru.<ref name=\"DFRL\">{{cite web|author1=Digital Forensic Research Lab|title=Breaking Down the Surkov Leaks \u2013 DFRLab|url=https://medium.com/dfrlab/breaking-down-the-surkov-leaks-b2feec1423cb#.t4wz7vsnx|website=Medium|publisher=Atlantic Council|date=25 October 2016}}</ref> The Kremlin suggested that the leaked documents were fake.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Walker|first1=Shaun|title=Kremlin puppet master's leaked emails are price of return to political frontline|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2016/oct/26/kremlin-puppet-masters-leaked-emails-vladislav-surkov-east-ukraine|work=The Guardian|date=26 October 2016}}</ref>\n\nThe emails illustrate Russian plans to politically destabilize Ukraine and the coordination of affairs with major opposition leaders in separatist east Ukraine.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Murdock|first1=Jason|title=Surkov leaks: Thousands of hacked emails reportedly from high-ranking Kremlin official published|url=http://www.ibtimes.co.uk/surkov-leaks-thousands-hacked-emails-high-ranking-kremlin-officials-published-1588645|work=International Business Times UK|date=27 October 2016}}</ref> The document release included a document sent by [[Denis Pushilin]], former Chair of the [[People's Soviet of the Donetsk People's Republic|People's Soviet]] of the [[Donetsk People's Republic]], listing casualties that occurred from 26 May to\u200a 6 June 2014.<ref name=\"DFRL\"/> It also included a 22-page outline of \"a plan to support nationalist and separatist politicians and to encourage early parliamentary elections in Ukraine, all with the aim of undermining the government in Kiev.\"<ref>{{cite news|last1=Standish|first1=Reid|title=Hacked: Putin Aide's Emails Detail Alleged Plot to Destabilize Ukraine|url=https://foreignpolicy.com/2016/10/25/hacked-putin-aides-emails-detail-alleged-plot-to-destabilize-kiev-surkov-ukraine-leaks/|work=Foreign Policy|date=25 October 2016}}</ref>\n\n{{See also|Sergey Glazyev#Glazyev tapes}}\n\n== Criticism and depictions ==\nBefore the 2010 U.S.-Russia \"Civil Society to Civil Society\" (C2C) summit, a [[United States House of Representatives|U.S. House of Representatives]] representative for [[Florida|the state of Florida]]'s [[Florida's 27th congressional district|27th district]], [[Ileana Ros-Lehtinen]] ([[Republican Party (United States)|R]]), was the lead signatory of a written petition which called upon the [[Presidency of Barack Obama|Obama administration]] to suspend U.S. participation in the summit until Surkov was replaced as a delegate for the Russian side. In an interview with [[Radio Free Europe/Radio Liberty|Radio Free Europe]], Ros-Lehtinen explained that she objected to Surkov's attendance as she views him as \"one of the main propagators of [[Media freedom in Russia|limiting freedom of speech in Russia]], intimidating Russian journalists and representatives of [[Political parties in Russia|opposition political parties]]\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.rferl.org/a/today_on_svoboda/1952096.html|title=Controversy Over Civil Society Representative Appointment, Human Rights Lawyer Detained|last=|first=|date=8 February 2010|website=RadioFreeEurope/RadioLiberty|publisher=|access-date=20 November 2016}}</ref> However, the summit went ahead despite her objections.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ethicsrussia.org/index.php/what-we-do/activities-through-2011/projects-activities2/135-report-on-us-russia-c2c-summit-is-released|title=December 2010 Report on US-Russia C2C Summit is released|last=|first=|date=|website=www.ethicsrussia.org|publisher=Center for Business Ethics and Corporate Governance|access-date=20 November 2016}}</ref> A 2007 [[Open Source Center]] \"Media Aid\" document identifies the Russian ''ura.ru'' information website as reportedly having links to Surkov.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://fas.org/irp/dni/osc/russian-media.pdf |title=Source Descriptors of Key Russian Media |publisher=[[Open Source Center]] |date=6 December 2007 |access-date=22 April 2017 |page=15 |website=fas.org |quote=ura.ru [...] reportedly has links to Kremlin aide Surkov }}</ref>\n\nInside Russia, Surkov has drawn criticism from activists and opposition groups: In [[2010 in Russia|September 2010]], [[Lyudmila Alexeyeva]] appealed to then-president [[Dmitry Medvedev]] to dismiss him.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://kommersant.ru/doc/1554113|title=\u0423 \u043f\u0440\u0430\u0432\u043e\u0437\u0430\u0449\u0438\u0442\u043d\u0438\u043a\u043e\u0432 \u0433\u043e\u0442\u043e\u0432\u043e \u043f\u0440\u043e\u0448\u0435\u043d\u0438\u0435 \u043e\u0431 \u043e\u0442\u0441\u0442\u0430\u0432\u043a\u0435|last=\u0422\u0438\u0440\u043c\u0430\u0441\u0442\u044d|first=\u041c\u0430\u0440\u0438\u044f-\u041b\u0443\u0438\u0437\u0430|date=12 September 2010|work=|last2=\u0422\u0438\u0440\u043c\u0430\u0441\u0442\u044d|first2=\u041c\u0430\u0440\u0438\u044f-\u041b\u0443\u0438\u0437\u0430|newspaper=\u0413\u0430\u0437\u0435\u0442\u0430 \"\u041a\u043e\u043c\u043c\u0435\u0440\u0441\u0430\u043d\u0442\u044a\"|issue=228|pages=3|language=Russian|access-date=20 November 2016|via=}}</ref> Opposition leaders [[Boris Nemtsov]] ([[Solidarnost]]), [[Vladimir Milov]] ([[Democratic Choice of Russia|Democratic Choice]]), and [[Vladimir Ryzhkov]] ([[People's Freedom Party]]) jointly demanded his resignation over policies perceived to threaten freedom of the press and journalists in Russia.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.polit.ru/news/2010/11/09/Surkov/|title=\u0418\u0437\u0431\u0438\u0435\u043d\u0438\u0435 \u041a\u0430\u0448\u0438\u043d\u0430: \u043e\u043f\u043f\u043e\u0437\u0438\u0446\u0438\u043e\u043d\u0435\u0440\u044b \u041d\u0435\u043c\u0446\u043e\u0432, \u0420\u044b\u0436\u043a\u043e\u0432 \u0438 \u041c\u0438\u043b\u043e\u0432 \u043f\u043e\u0442\u0440\u0435\u0431\u043e\u0432\u0430\u043b\u0438 \u043e\u0442\u0441\u0442\u0430\u0432\u043a\u0438 \u0421\u0443\u0440\u043a\u043e\u0432\u0430 \u2013 \u041f\u041e\u041b\u0418\u0422.\u0420\u0423|website=www.polit.ru|access-date=20 November 2016}}</ref> [[Igor Strelkov (officer)|Igor Ivanovich Strelkov]], who played a key role in the [[Russian military intervention in Ukraine (2014\u2013present)|Russian military intervention in Ukraine]], referred to Surkov as a \"notorious\" person who \"focuses only on destruction...as in [[South Ossetia]] and other regions where he focused on [[looting]] rather than aide\" ({{Lang-ru|\u044d\u0442\u043e \u043b\u044e\u0434\u0438, \u043a\u043e\u0442\u043e\u0440\u044b\u0435 \u043d\u0430\u0446\u0435\u043b\u0435\u043d\u044b \u0442\u043e\u043b\u044c\u043a\u043e \u043d\u0430 \u0440\u0430\u0437\u0440\u0443\u0448\u0435\u043d\u0438\u0435...\u0432 \u042e\u0436\u043d\u043e\u0439 \u041e\u0441\u0435\u0442\u0438\u0438, \u0432 \u0434\u0440\u0443\u0433\u0438\u0445 \u0440\u0435\u0433\u0438\u043e\u043d\u0430\u0445, \u0432\u0435\u0437\u0434\u0435, \u0433\u0434\u0435 \u043e\u043d \u043d\u0430\u0445\u043e\u0434\u0438\u043b\u0441\u044f...\u0440\u0430\u0437\u0433\u0440\u0430\u0431\u043b\u0435\u043d\u0438\u0435\u043c \u0432\u043c\u0435\u0441\u0442\u043e \u0440\u0435\u0430\u043b\u044c\u043d\u043e\u0439 \u043f\u043e\u043c\u043e\u0449\u0438.|link=no}}).<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://novorossiia.ru/main/13879-g-n.html|title=\u042d\u043a\u0441\u043a\u043b\u044e\u0437\u0438\u0432\u043d\u043e\u0435 \u0438\u043d\u0442\u0435\u0440\u0432\u044c\u044e \u0418. \u0421\u0442\u0440\u0435\u043b\u043a\u043e\u0432\u0430: \"\u0421\u0440\u0430\u0436\u0430\u044f\u0441\u044c \u0437\u0430 \u041d\u043e\u0432\u043e\u0440\u043e\u0441\u0441\u0438\u044e, \u043c\u044b \u0441\u0440\u0430\u0436\u0430\u0435\u043c\u0441\u044f \u0437\u0430 \u0420\u043e\u0441\u0441\u0438\u044e\".|last=|first=|date=|website=novorossiia.ru|publisher=[[Novorossiya]]|access-date=20 November 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn 2013, Surkov was characterized by ''[[The Economist]]'' as the engineer of \"a system of make-believe\", \"a land of imitation political parties, stage-managed media and fake social movements\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.economist.com/news/europe/21577421-what-departure-vladislav-surkov-means-government-ideologues-exit|title=An ideologue's exit|date=11 May 2013|newspaper=The Economist|issn=0013-0613|access-date=20 November 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn [[Western media]] outside Russia, a vocal and eloquent [[critic]] of Surkov and of the [[Presidency of Vladimir Putin|administration of Vladimir Putin]] in general has been [[Peter Pomerantsev]]. Pomerantsev has written [[op-ed]]s in ''[[The Atlantic]]'',<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theatlantic.com/international/archive/2014/09/russia-putin-revolutionizing-information-warfare/379880/|title=Russia and the Menace of Unreality|last=Pomerantsev|first=Peter|date=9 September 2014|work=|newspaper=The Atlantic|language=en-US|access-date=20 November 2016|via=}}</ref> ''[[The New York Times]]'',<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2014/12/12/opinion/russias-ideology-there-is-no-truth.html|title=Russia's Ideology: There Is No Truth|last=Pomerantsev|first=Peter|date=11 December 2014|newspaper=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|access-date=20 November 2016}}</ref> and the ''[[London Review of Books]]''<ref name=\"LOB01\" /><ref name=\":1\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.lrb.co.uk/blog/2013/05/08/peter-pomerantsev/the-empty-chair/|title=Peter Pomerantsev: Goodbye Surkov|website=LRB blog|access-date=20 November 2016}}</ref> accusing Surkov, \"Putin's chief [[Ideology|ideologue]]\" with \"unsurpassed influence over Russian politics\", of turning Russia into a \"[[Managed Democracy|managed democracy]]\", and of reducing [[Politics of Russia|Russian politics]] to nothing but \"[[Postmodern theatre|postmodernist theatre]]\". In a talk before the [[Legatum Institute]], Pomerantsev, along with [[Pavel Khodorkovsky]], termed Russia a \"[[postmodern]] [[dictatorship]]\".<ref>{{Citation|last=|title=Russia: A Postmodern Dictatorship? With Pavel Khodorkovsky & Peter Pomerantsev|date=14 October 2013|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=qMIHmzgzVBU|publication-date=|publisher=Legatum Institute|accessdate=20 November 2016}}</ref>\n\n=== Rumored pseudonym of Nathan Dubovitsky ===\nOn 13 August 2009, Russian business newspaper ''[[Vedomosti]]'' reported that an anonymous source told them that a recently released novel, ''Close to Zero'' (''{{Lang-ru|[[:ru:\u041e\u043a\u043e\u043b\u043e\u043d\u043e\u043b\u044f|\u041e\u043a\u043e\u043b\u043e\u043d\u043e\u043b\u044f]]|link=no}}''), was written by Surkov under the pseudonym Nathan Dubovitsky ({{Lang-ru|\u041d\u0430\u0442\u0430\u043d \u0414\u0443\u0431\u043e\u0432\u0438\u0446\u043a\u0438\u0439|link=no}}) in the magazine Russian Pioneer ({{Lang-ru|[[:ru:\u0420\u0443\u0441\u0441\u043a\u0438\u0439 \u043f\u0438\u043e\u043d\u0435\u0440|\u0420\u0443\u0441\u0441\u043a\u0438\u0439 \u043f\u0438\u043e\u043d\u0435\u0440]]|link=no}}). It was soon realized that the pseudonym is almost identical to the name of Surkov's second and current wife, Natalya Dubovitskaya ({{Lang-ru|\u041d\u0430\u0442\u0430\u043b\u044c\u044f \u0414\u0443\u0431\u043e\u0432\u0438\u0446\u043a\u0430\u044f|link=no}}).<ref name=\":3\" />\n\nIn a subsequent edition of ''Close to Zero'', Surkov would write a preface to it under his real name, but would continue to deny writing the main text. In the preface, Surkov writes two seemingly contradictory statements: \"The author of this novel is an unoriginal Hamlet-obsessed hack\"; and, \"this is the best book I have ever read\".<ref name=\"LOB01\" /> Furthermore, the debut performance of the [[Play (theatre)|theatrical version]] of the novel, [[Theatre director|directed]] by [[Kirill Serebrennikov]], was attended by Surkov.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.kp.ru/daily/25625.5/792155/|title=\"\u041e\u043a\u043e\u043b\u043e\u043d\u043e\u043b\u044f\": \u0447\u0451\u0440\u043d\u043e\u0435 \u043d\u0430 \u0447\u0451\u0440\u043d\u043e\u043c|last=Dementsova|first=Emilia|date=24 January 2011|work=|newspaper=[[Komsomolskaya Pravda]]|language=Russian|trans-title=\"Close to Zero\": Black on black|quote=And recently I attended a Kirill Serebrennikov play based on the novel \"Close to Zero\", the debut of which was attended by Surkov himself. (\u0418 \u0432\u043e\u0442 \u043d\u0435\u0434\u0430\u0432\u043d\u043e \u0432\u044b\u0448\u0435\u043b \u0441\u043f\u0435\u043a\u0442\u0430\u043a\u043b\u044c \u041a\u0438\u0440\u0438\u043b\u043b\u0430 \u0421\u0435\u0440\u0435\u0431\u0440\u0435\u043d\u0438\u043a\u043e\u0432\u0430 \u043f\u043e \u0440\u043e\u043c\u0430\u043d\u0443 \u00ab\u041e\u043a\u043e\u043b\u043e\u043d\u043e\u043b\u044f\u00bb, \u043d\u0430 \u043f\u0440\u0435\u043c\u044c\u0435\u0440\u0435 \u043a\u043e\u0442\u043e\u0440\u043e\u0433\u043e \u043f\u0440\u0438\u0441\u0443\u0442\u0441\u0442\u0432\u043e\u0432\u0430\u043b \u0438 \u0441\u0430\u043c \u0421\u0443\u0440\u043a\u043e\u0432.)|access-date=20 November 2016|via=}}</ref>\n\nThe novel, which has the [[English language]] subtitle \"gangsta fiction\", has as its [[protagonist]] a man by the name of Yegor Samokhodov. Samokhodov's occupation is [[public relations]], and he is tasked with managing the reputation of a [[List of current heads of federal subjects of Russia|regional governor]]. First, he hires a writer to [[Ghostwriter|ghostwrite]] a piece of [[poetry]] to be published under the name of the governor without disclosing the ghostwriting, so that the governor may win an award and seem clever to his constituents. He then [[Bribery|bribes]] a [[Journalist|newspaper reporter]] to \"correct\" stories that portray the governor negatively, such as allegations that a [[factory]] of a [[Nepotism|relative of his]] is [[Air pollution|releasing chemicals into the air]] that harm local children.<ref name=\":2\" /> The [[publishing houses]] and public relations firms in the novel are intensely violent, with each company having its own [[Street gang|gang]] and [[wikt:turf war|turf war]]s being fought over the [[Publishing rights|rights to publish]] or [[Talent agent|represent]] such acclaimed [[Russian authors]] as [[Alexander Pushkin]] and [[Vladimir Nabokov]].<ref name=\"LOB01\" /> Peter Pomerantsev described the book as \"exactly the sort of book [[Nashi (youth movement)|Surkov's youth groups]] burn on [[Red Square]].\"<ref name=\"LOB01\" /> ''The Economist'' wrote that the novel \"expos[ed] the vices of the system [Surkov] himself had created\".<ref>[http://www.economist.com/node/21541444 \"The long life of Homo sovieticus\"]. ''The Economist''. 10 December 2011 (issue date). Retrieved 8 December 2011.</ref>\n\nOther works authored under the name Nathan Dubovitsky, all published in Russian Pioneer, that are rumored to be the work of Surkov are:\n* ''The Little Car and the Bicycle [gaga saga]'' ({{Lang-ru|\u041c\u0430\u0448\u0438\u043d\u043a\u0430 \u0438 \u0412\u0435\u043b\u0438\u043a [gaga saga]|Mashinka i Velik [gaga saga]|link=no}}) (2012) <ref>{{Cite news|url=http://grandmotherafrica.com/cloudless-sky-short-story-nathan-dubovitsky/|title=A Cloudless Sky \u2013 A Short Story By Nathan Dubovitsky \u2013 Grandmother Africa|last=Nefekare|first=Jehuti|date=2 February 2015|newspaper=Grandmother Africa|language=en-US|access-date=20 November 2016}}</ref>\n* ''Uncle Vanya [cover version]'' (2014) ({{Lang-ru|\u0414\u044f\u0434\u044f \u0412\u0430\u043d\u044f [cover version]|link=no}})<ref>http://ruspioner.ru/cool/m/single/4103</ref>\n* ''Without Sky'' (2014) ({{Lang-ru|\u0411\u0435\u0437 \u043d\u0435\u0431\u0430|link=no}})<ref name=\":1\" />\n*''Ultranormality'' (2017) (Russian: \u0423\u043b\u044c\u0442\u0440\u0430\u043d\u043e\u0440\u043c\u0430\u043b\u044c\u043d\u043e\u0441\u0442\u044c)\n\n=== Influence outside Russia ===\nSome outside Russia, such as Ned Reskinoff of [[ThinkProgress]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://medium.com/@resnikoff/phantasmagoria-3beac7fe516d|title=Phantasmagoria|last=Resnikoff|first=Ned|date=26 September 2016|website=Medium|access-date=19 November 2016}}</ref> and [[Adam Curtis]] in the [[BBC News|BBC]] documentary ''[[HyperNormalisation]]'',<ref name=\":6\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/iplayer/episode/p04b183c/adam-curtis-hypernormalisation|title=Adam Curtis, HyperNormalisation|website=BBC iPlayer|access-date=19 November 2016}}</ref> have claimed that Surkov's unique blend of politics and theatre have begun to affect countries outside of Russia,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/p074j379|title=BBC Radio 4 - Seriously..., The Puppet Master \u2013 Episode 1. Snipers|publisher=BBC|language=en-GB|access-date=5 April 2019}}</ref> most notably the United States with the selection of [[Donald Trump]] for the [[Republican Party presidential primaries, 2016|2016 US Republican nomination]] and Trump's [[Donald Trump presidential campaign, 2016|subsequent campaign]] and [[2016 United States presidential election|election victory]].\n\nIn an editorial for the ''[[London Review of Books]]'' quoted by Curtis, [[Peter Pomerantsev]] describes Putin's Russia thus:\n\n{{Quote|text=In contemporary Russia, unlike the old USSR or present-day North Korea, the stage is constantly changing: the country is a dictatorship in the morning, a democracy at lunch, an oligarchy by suppertime, while, backstage, oil companies are expropriated, journalists killed, billions siphoned away. Surkov is at the centre of the show, sponsoring nationalist skinheads one moment, backing human rights groups the next. It's a strategy of power based on keeping any opposition there may be constantly confused, a ceaseless shape-shifting that is unstoppable because it's indefinable.|sign=[[Peter Pomerantsev]]|source=in \"Putin's Rasputin\", ''[[London Review of Books]]'' issue of 20 October 2011<ref name=LOB01/>}}\n\nCurtis claims that Trump used a similar strategy to become [[president of the United States]], and hints that Trump's Surkovian origins caused Putin to express his admiration for Trump in [[Russian media]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/2016/oct/09/adam-curtis-donald-trump-documentary-hypernormalisation|title=Adam Curtis continues search for the hidden forces behind a century of chaos|last=Adams|first=Tim|date=9 October 2016|newspaper=The Guardian|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077|access-date=20 November 2016}}</ref><ref>{{Cite AV media|title=[[HyperNormalisation]]|year=2016|medium=BBC iPlayer|people=[[Adam Curtis]]}}</ref>\n\nSurkov has boasted that \"Russia is playing with the West\u2019s minds\", \"They don't know how to deal with their own changed consciousness.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/europe/putin-russia-kremlin-vladislav-surkov-grey-cardinal-moscow-a8773661.html|title=Russia is 'playing with the West's minds' says Putin advisor|newspaper=[[The Independent]]|last=Carroll|first=Oliver|date=12 February 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nSurkov has married twice. His first marriage, to Yulia Petrovna Vishnevskaya ({{Lang-ru|\u042e\u043b\u0438\u044f \u041f\u0435\u0442\u0440\u043e\u0432\u043d\u0430 \u0412\u0438\u0448\u043d\u0435\u0432\u0441\u043a\u0430\u044f|link=no}}) in 1987, ended in divorce in 1996. In his second marriage, Surkov married Natalya Dubovitskaya, his secretary when he was an executive at the [[Bank Menatep|Menatep]] bank, in a civil ceremony in 1998.<ref name=\"lenta.ru\"/><ref>[http://www.anticompromat.org/surkov/surkbio.html Surkov bio] anticompromat.ru</ref><ref name=\":4\">{{Cite web|url= http://www.uznayvse.ru/znamenitosti/biografiya-vladislav-surkov.html|title= \u0412\u043b\u0430\u0434\u0438\u0441\u043b\u0430\u0432 \u0421\u0443\u0440\u043a\u043e\u0432 \u0431\u0438\u043e\u0433\u0440\u0430\u0444\u0438\u044f, \u0444\u043e\u0442\u043e, \u0435\u0433\u043e \u0436\u0435\u043d\u0430 \u0438 \u0441\u0435\u043c\u044c\u044f|last= |first= |date= |website= www.uznayvse.ru|publisher= |language= Russian|trans-title= Vladislav Surkov, biography, photos, his wife and family|access-date= 20 November 2016}}</ref> Surkov has four children: [[Artem Surkov|Artem]] ({{Lang-ru|\u0410\u0440\u0442\u0451\u043c|link=no}}; born 15 October 1993),<ref name=\":4\"/><ref>{{cite web|title= \u0421\u0443\u0440\u043a\u043e\u0432 \u0410\u0440\u0442\u0451\u043c \u041e\u043b\u0435\u0433\u043e\u0432\u0438\u0447 (Artem Olegovich Surkov)|url= http://wrestrus.ru/users/5131|website= Russian Wrestling Federation|publisher= \u0424\u0435\u0434\u0435\u0440\u0430\u0446\u0438\u044f \u0441\u043f\u043e\u0440\u0442\u0438\u0432\u043d\u043e\u0439 \u0431\u043e\u0440\u044c\u0431\u044b \u0420\u043e\u0441\u0441\u0438\u0438|accessdate= 23 November 2016}}</ref> the biological child of Yulia he adopted during his first marriage; and Roman ({{Lang-ru|\u0420\u043e\u043c\u0430\u043d|link=no}}; born 2002),<ref name=\":7\">{{Cite web|url= http://kremlin.ru/structure/administration/income-reports|title= Data on income, property and property obligations of federal officials of the Presidential Administration and the Security Council of Russia, as well as their spouses and minor children for the period from 1 January 2010 to 31 December 2010 (\u0421\u0432\u0435\u0434\u0435\u043d\u0438\u044f \u043e \u0434\u043e\u0445\u043e\u0434\u0430\u0445, \u043e\u0431 \u0438\u043c\u0443\u0449\u0435\u0441\u0442\u0432\u0435 \u0438 \u043e\u0431\u044f\u0437\u0430\u0442\u0435\u043b\u044c\u0441\u0442\u0432\u0430\u0445 \u0438\u043c\u0443\u0449\u0435\u0441\u0442\u0432\u0435\u043d\u043d\u043e\u0433\u043e \u0445\u0430\u0440\u0430\u043a\u0442\u0435\u0440\u0430 \u0444\u0435\u0434\u0435\u0440\u0430\u043b\u044c\u043d\u044b\u0445 \u0433\u043e\u0441\u0443\u0434\u0430\u0440\u0441\u0442\u0432\u0435\u043d\u043d\u044b\u0445 \u0441\u043b\u0443\u0436\u0430\u0449\u0438\u0445 \u0410\u0434\u043c\u0438\u043d\u0438\u0441\u0442\u0440\u0430\u0446\u0438\u0438 \u041f\u0440\u0435\u0437\u0438\u0434\u0435\u043d\u0442\u0430 \u0438 \u0430\u043f\u043f\u0430\u0440\u0430\u0442\u0430 \u0421\u043e\u0432\u0435\u0442\u0430 \u0411\u0435\u0437\u043e\u043f\u0430\u0441\u043d\u043e\u0441\u0442\u0438 \u0420\u043e\u0441\u0441\u0438\u0438, \u0430 \u0442\u0430\u043a\u0436\u0435 \u0438\u0445 \u0441\u0443\u043f\u0440\u0443\u0433\u043e\u0432 \u0438 \u043d\u0435\u0441\u043e\u0432\u0435\u0440\u0448\u0435\u043d\u043d\u043e\u043b\u0435\u0442\u043d\u0438\u0445 \u0434\u0435\u0442\u0435\u0439 \u0437\u0430 \u043f\u0435\u0440\u0438\u043e\u0434 \u0441 1 \u044f\u043d\u0432\u0430\u0440\u044f 2010\u0433. \u043f\u043e 31 \u0434\u0435\u043a\u0430\u0431\u0440\u044f 2010\u0433.)|last= |first= |date= 2010|website= Official [[Kremlin]] Website|publisher= |access-date= }}</ref> Maria ({{Lang-ru|\u041c\u0430\u0440\u0438\u044f|link= no}}; born 2004),<ref name=\":7\" /> and Timur ({{Lang-ru|\u0422\u0438\u043c\u0443\u0440|link= no}}; born 2010),<ref name=\":7\" /> biological children of himself and Natalya.<ref name=\":4\" />\n\nSurkov has composed songs<ref name=LOB01/> and written texts for the Russian rock-musician Vadim Samoylov, ex-member of the band [[Agatha Christie (band)|Agata Kristi]] ({{lang-ru|\u0410\u0433\u0430\u0442\u0430 \u041a\u0440\u0438\u0441\u0442\u0438}}). He speaks English and is fond of poets of the [[Beat Generation]] such as [[Allen Ginsberg]].<ref name=RE01>\nFaulconbridge, Guy [https://www.reuters.com/article/2011/09/16/us-russia-prokhorov-surkov-idUSTRE78F2TB20110916 \"Kremlin \"puppet master\" faces errant oligarch\"]. Reuters. 16 September 2011. Retrieved 21 September 2011.\n</ref>\n\n==Honours and awards==\n* [[Order of Merit for the Fatherland]], 3rd class (13 November 2003) \u2013 for outstanding contribution to strengthening Russian statehood and many years of diligent work\n* Gratitude of the President of the Russian Federation (18 January 2010, 12 June 2004 and 8 July 2003) \u2013 for active participation in the preparation of the President's address to the Federal Assembly of the Russian Federation\n* Medal of PA Stolypin, 2nd class (21 September 2011)\n* Diploma of the [[Central Election Commission of the Russian Federation]] (2 April 2008) \u2013 for active support and substantial assistance in organizing and conducting the elections of the President of the Russian Federation\n* State Councillor of the Russian Federation, 1st class\n\n==See also==\n*[[Mikhail Lesin]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* Bovt, Georgii. \"Vladislav Surkov: A Pragmatic Idealism.\" ''Russian Politics & Law'' 46#5 (2008): 33\u201340.\n*  M\u00e4kinen, Sirke. \"Surkovian narrative on the future of Russia: making Russia a world leader.\" ''Journal of Communist Studies and Transition Politics'' 27#2 (2011): 143\u2013165.\n* Sakwa, Richard. \"Russian Political Culture Through the Eyes of Vladislav Surkov\" ''Russian Politics & Law'' 46.5 (2008): 3\u20137.\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Vladislav Surkov}}\n* [http://en.kremlin.ru/catalog/persons/2/biography Official record]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20140427010955/http://russiaprofile.org/bg_people/resources_whoiswho_alphabet_s_surkov.html Russia Profile Who's Who]\n* [https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/p074j379 The Puppet Master - \"This is the story of the most powerful man you\u2019ve never heard of\" - BBC Radio 4 Podcast \"Seriously\u2026\"]\n* [http://users2.wsj.com/lmda/do/checkLogin?mg=wsj-users2&url=http%3A%2F%2Fonline.wsj.com%2Farticle%2FSB116646992809753610.html%3Fmod%3DITPWSJ_1 Surkov: In His Own Words. The Wall Street Journal. 18 December 2006]\n* [http://lenta.ru/lib/14159273/full.htm Biography @ Lenta.ru]\n* [https://www.bbc.co.uk/blogs/adamcurtis/2012/01/the_years_of_stagnation_and_th.html The Years of Stagnation and the Poodles of Power], [[Adam Curtis]] blog at BBC\n* [http://www.lrb.co.uk/v33/n20/peter-pomerantsev/putins-rasputin Putin's Rasputin], by [[Peter Pomerantsev]] in [[London Review of Books]]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20150201203715/http://allpersons.name/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=528&Itemid=12 Biography Surkov] (Russian)\n\n{{Current Russian Cabinet}}\n{{Ukrainian crisis navbox}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Surkov, Vladislav Yuryevich}}\n[[Category:Aides to the President of Russia]]\n[[Category:GRU officers]]\n[[Category:Russian businesspeople]]\n[[Category:Medvedev Administration personnel]]\n[[Category:United Russia politicians]]\n[[Category:People of the annexation of Crimea by the Russian Federation]]\n[[Category:Pro-Russian people of the 2014 pro-Russian unrest in Ukraine]]\n[[Category:Moscow Institute of Steel and Alloys alumni]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Order \"For Merit to the Fatherland\", 3rd class]]\n[[Category:People from Chaplyginsky District]]\n[[Category:People from Shalinsky District, Chechen Republic]]\n[[Category:People of the Ukrainian crisis]]\n[[Category:Russian people of Chechen descent]]\n[[Category:1964 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:20th-century Russian politicians]]\n[[Category:21st-century Russian politicians]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2020}}\n{{Expand Ukrainian|\u0421\u0443\u0440\u043a\u043e\u0432 \u0412\u043b\u0430\u0434\u0438\u0441\u043b\u0430\u0432 \u042e\u0440\u0456\u0439\u043e\u0432\u0438\u0447|date=February 2020}}\n{{Eastern Slavic name|Yuryevich|Surkov}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| image        = Vladislav Surkov 7 May 2013.jpeg\n| imagesize    = 220px\n| caption      = Surkov in May 2012\n| order        = Assistant to the [[President of Russia|President of the Russian Federation]]\n| term_start   = 20 September 2013\n| term_end     = 18 February 2020\n| president1   = [[Vladimir Putin]]\n| office2      = [[Deputy Chairman of the Government of the Russian Federation|Deputy Prime Minister of Russia]] \u2014 Head of the Government Executive Office\n| term_start2  = 21 May 2012\n| term_end2    = 8 May 2013\n| primeminister2 = [[Dmitry Medvedev]]\n| predecessor2 = [[Vyacheslav Volodin]]\n| successor2   = [[Sergey Prikhodko]]\n| office3      = [[Deputy Chairman of the Government of the Russian Federation|Deputy Prime Minister of Russia]] \n| term_start3  = 27 December 2011\n| term_end3    = 21 May 2012\n| primeminister3 = [[Vladimir Putin]]<br />[[Dmitry Medvedev]]\n| predecessor3 = \n| successor3   = \n| office4      = First Deputy Chief of Staff of the [[Presidential Administration of Russia]] \n| term_start4  = 15 May 2008\n| term_end4    = 27 December 2011\n| president4   = [[Dmitry Medvedev]]\n| office5      = Deputy Chief of Staff of the [[Presidential Administration of Russia]] \n| term_start5  = 3 August 1999\n| term_end5    = 12 May 2008\n| president5   = [[Boris Yeltsin]]<br/ >[[Vladimir Putin]]\n| birth_name   = Aslambek Andarbekovich Dudayev\n| birth_date   = {{Birth date and age|1962|9|21|df=y}}<br />{{Birth date and age|1964|9|21|df=y}} (sources differ)\n| birth_place  = [[Soviet Union]]{{efn|Surkov's official biography claims his birth place as Solntsevo, [[Lipetsk Oblast]], [[Russian Soviet Federative Socialist Republic|Russian SFSR]], however other sources claim his birth place as [[Shali, Chechen Republic|Shali]], [[Checheno-Ingush Autonomous Soviet Socialist Republic|Checheno-Ingush-ASSR]].}}\n| party        = [[United Russia]]\n| spouse       = {{marriage|Yulia Vishnevskaya|1987|1996|end=div}}<br />{{marriage|Natalya Dubovitskaya<br>|1998}}\n| children     = 4\n| alma_mater   = [[International University in Moscow]]\n| profession   = \n| signature    = Signature of Vladislav Surkov.png\n}}\n\n'''Vladislav Yuryevich Surkov''' ({{lang-ru|\u0412\u043b\u0430\u0434\u0438\u0441\u043b\u0430\u0301\u0432 \u042e\u0301\u0440\u044c\u0435\u0432\u0438\u0447 \u0421\u0443\u0440\u043a\u043e\u0301\u0432}}, [[n\u00e9]] '''Aslambek Andarbekovich Dudayev''', \u0410\u0441\u043b\u0430\u043c\u0431\u0435\u0301\u043a \u0410\u043d\u0434\u0430\u0440\u0431\u0435\u043a\u043e\u0432\u0438\u0447 \u0414\u0443\u0434\u0430\u0301\u0435\u0432; born 21 September 1962 or 1964, sources differ)<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.gazeta.ru/politics/elections2007/parts/1477554.shtml|title=\u0411\u0435\u0441\u043f\u0430\u0440\u0442\u0438\u0439\u043d\u044b\u0439 \u0438\u0434\u0435\u043e\u043b\u043e\u0433 \u0412\u043b\u0430\u0434\u0438\u0441\u043b\u0430\u0432 \u0421\u0443\u0440\u043a\u043e\u0432|date=16 May 2007|work=[[Gazeta.ru]]|accessdate=1 April 2009}}{{dead link|date=April 2020}}</ref> is a Russian businessman and politician. He was First Deputy Chief of the [[Presidential Administration of Russia|Russian Presidential Administration]] from 1999 to 2011, during which time he was often viewed as the main ideologist of the [[Kremlin]] who proposed and implemented the concept of [[sovereign democracy]] in Russia. From December 2011 until May 2013, Surkov served as the Russian Federation's Deputy Prime Minister.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://en.kremlin.ru/events/president/news/14156|title=Vladislav Surkov has been appointed Deputy Prime Minister|website=President of&nbsp;Russia}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | title = Russian President Accepts Resignation Of Deputy PM Surkov | url = http://www.rferl.org/content/russia-deputy-pm-surkov-quits/24980174.html | work = [[Radio Free Europe]] |  date = 8 May 2013}}</ref> After his resignation, Surkov returned to the Presidential Executive Office and became a personal adviser of [[Vladimir Putin]] on relationships with [[Abkhazia]], [[South Ossetia]] and [[Ukraine]].<ref name=\"forbes.ua\">{{cite web | last = \u0412\u0438\u043d\u043e\u043a\u0443\u0440\u043e\u0432\u0430 | first = \u0415\u043a\u0430\u0442\u0435\u0440\u0438\u043d\u0430 | title = \u0427\u0435\u043c \u0412\u043b\u0430\u0434\u0438\u0441\u043b\u0430\u0432 \u0421\u0443\u0440\u043a\u043e\u0432 \u0437\u0430\u0439\u043c\u0435\u0442\u0441\u044f \u0432 \u0423\u043a\u0440\u0430\u0438\u043d\u0435 | url = http://forbes.ua/nation/1358330-chem-vladislav-surkov-zajmetsya-v-ukraine | work = [[Forbes|Forbes.ua]] | date = 20 September 2013}}</ref> He was fired from this duty by presidential order in February 2020.<ref name=\":8\">{{Cite web|url=https://meduza.io/en/news/2020/02/18/putin-officially-fires-top-political-curator-vladislav-surkov|title=Putin officially fires top political aide Vladislav Surkov|website=meduza.io|access-date=18 February 2020}}</ref>\n\nSurkov is perceived by many to be a [[\u00c9minence grise|key figure with much power and influence]] in the administration of Vladimir Putin.<ref name=\"RE01\" /><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.ibtimes.co.uk/vladislav-surkov-who-vladimir-putins-grey-cardinal-1588913|title=Vladislav Surkov: Who is Vladimir Putin's 'grey cardinal'?|last=Thomas|first=Matt|date=29 October 2016|newspaper=International Business Times UK|access-date=21 November 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"LOB01\" /> According to ''[[The Moscow Times]]'', this perception is not dependent on the official title Surkov might hold at any one time in the Putin government.<ref name=\":5\">{{Cite news|url=https://themoscowtimes.com/articles/same-old-kremlin-same-old-surkov-28364|title=Same Old Kremlin, Same Old Surkov|last=Ryzhkov|first=Vladimir|date=7 October 2013|work=[[The Moscow Times]]|quote=Surkov played the decisive role in raising Kadyrov to his current post. For his part, Kadyrov refers to Surkov as his \"sworn brother\" and even has a portrait of Surkov hanging in his office in [[Grozny]].\"  and  \"...a person's formal job title in Russia never matches the actual authority they wield.|access-date=20 November 2016|via=}}</ref> [[BBC]] [[documentary film]]maker [[Adam Curtis]] credits Surkov's blend of [[Theatre|theater]] and [[politics]] with keeping Putin, [[Tandemocracy (Russia)|and Putin's chosen successors]], in power since 2000.<ref name=\":6\" />\n\nJournalists in Russia and abroad have speculated that Surkov writes under the [[pseudonym]] '''Nathan Dubovitsky''', although [[Moscow Kremlin|the Kremlin]] denies it.<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.vedomosti.ru/politics/articles/2009/08/13/vladislav-surkov-stal-pisatelem|title=\u0412\u043b\u0430\u0434\u0438\u0441\u043b\u0430\u0432 \u0421\u0443\u0440\u043a\u043e\u0432 \u0441\u0442\u0430\u043b \u043f\u0438\u0441\u0430\u0442\u0435\u043b\u0435\u043c?|last=Glikin|first=Maksim|date=13 August 2009|work=[[Vedomosti]]|last2=Kholmogorova|first2=Vera|trans-title=Has Vladislav Surkov become a writer?|quote=Published novel ''Close to Zero'' was probably written by Vladislav Surkov. (\u0418\u0437\u0434\u0430\u043d \u0440\u043e\u043c\u0430\u043d \u00ab\u041e\u043a\u043e\u043b\u043e\u043d\u043e\u043b\u044f\u00bb, \u043d\u0430\u043f\u0438\u0441\u0430\u043d\u043d\u044b\u0439 \u0441\u043a\u043e\u0440\u0435\u0435 \u0432\u0441\u0435\u0433\u043e \u0412\u043b\u0430\u0434\u0438\u0441\u043b\u0430\u0432\u043e\u043c \u0421\u0443\u0440\u043a\u043e\u0432\u044b\u043c.)|access-date=20 November 2016|via=}}</ref><ref name=\"Storey\" /><ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.lrb.co.uk/blog/2014/03/28/peter-pomerantsev/non-linear-war/|title=Peter Pomerantsev: Non-Linear War|website=LRB blog|access-date=20 November 2016}}</ref><ref name=\":2\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/europe/did-kremlin-political-chief-really-write-murky-gangster-novel-1771881.html|title=Did Kremlin political chief really write murky gangster novel?|date=14 August 2009|newspaper=The Independent|language=en-GB|access-date=20 November 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Early years==\nAccording to Surkov's official biography, he was born 21 September 1964 in Solntsevo, [[Lipetsk Oblast]], [[Russian Soviet Federative Socialist Republic|Russian SFSR]].<ref name=bio>{{cite web|title=\u0421\u0443\u0440\u043a\u043e\u0432 \u0412\u043b\u0430\u0434\u0438\u0441\u043b\u0430\u0432 \u042e\u0440\u044c\u0435\u0432\u0438\u0447 |url=http://www.government.ru/persons/171/ |work=government.ru |language=Russian |date=12 March 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120312213526/http://www.government.ru/persons/171/ |archivedate=12 March 2012 }}</ref><ref name=\"kremlinbio\">{{cite web | title = Surkov, Vladislav | url = http://en.kremlin.ru/catalog/persons/2/biography | work = kremlin.ru | accessdate = 12 October 2015}}</ref> As per other statements, he was born in [[Shali, Chechen Republic|Shali]], [[Checheno-Ingush Autonomous Soviet Socialist Republic|Checheno-Ingush ASSR]] in 1962.<ref name=\"scandaly\">{{cite web|last1=\u041c\u0430\u0440\u0438\u043d\u0438\u043d |first1=\u041c\u0430\u043a\u0441\u0438\u043c |last2=\u041a\u043e\u0441\u0430\u0440\u0435\u0432\u0430 |first2=\u0418\u0440\u0438\u043d\u0430 |url=http://scandaly.ru/news/news3611.html |title=\u0427\u0415\u0427\u0415\u041d\u0421\u041a\u041e\u0415 \u0414\u0415\u0422\u0421\u0422\u0412\u041e \u0421\u0423\u0420\u041a\u041e\u0412\u0410 |work=scandaly.ru |language=Russian |date=13 July 2005 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080518033227/http://scandaly.ru/news/news3611.html |archivedate=18 May 2008 }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|url=https://www.refworld.org/docid/5194b06b4.html|title=Intrigue and Gossip Overwhelm Moscow after Surkov's Downfall|publisher=[[Jamestown Foundation]]|journal=Eurasia Daily Monitor|volume=10|issue=88|last=Felgenhauer|first=Pavel|date=9 May 2013|access-date=11 April 2020}}</ref> His name when he was born is reported to be '''Aslambek Dudayev'''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://medium.com/@wmilam/the-theater-director-who-is-vladislav-surkov-9dd8a15e0efb|title=Who is Vladislav Surkov?|website=[[Medium (website)|Medium]]|last=Milam|first=Whitney|date=14 July 2018|access-date=25 July 2019}}</ref> His parents, the ethnic [[History of the Jews in Russia|Jewish Russian]] Zinaida Antonovna Surkova (born 1935) and the ethnic [[Chechens|Chechen]] Yuriy (\"Andarbek\") Danil'bekovich Dudayev (born 1942), were school teachers in [[Shalinsky District, Chechen Republic|Duba-yurt]], Checheno-Ingush ASSR.<ref name=\"scandaly\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=https://worldview.stratfor.com/article/kremlin-wars-special-series-part-4-surkov-presses-home|title=The Kremlin Wars (Special Series), Part 4: Surkov Presses Home|website=[[Stratfor]]|date=27 October 2009|url-access=subscription|access-date=11 April 2020}}</ref> Following the separation of his parents, his mother moved to [[Lipetsk]] and he was baptized into [[Eastern Orthodox Christianity]].<ref name=\"mtimes\">{{cite news| title = 5 Facts About Vladislav Surkov | url = http://www.themoscowtimes.com/news/article/5-facts-about-vladislav-surkov/479739.html | work = [[The Moscow Times]] | date = 13 May 2013}}</ref> In an interview published in June 2005 in the German magazine ''[[Der Spiegel]]'', Surkov stated that his father was ethnic Chechen and that he spent the first five years of his life in Chechnya,<ref>[http://www.spiegel.de/spiegel/0,1518,361084,00.html 'Der Westen muss uns nicht lieben']. Uwe Von Klu\u00dfmann. Walter Mayr. [[Der Spiegel]]. 20 June 2005. Quote: \"Ich selbst habe die ersten f\u00fcnf Jahre meines Lebens in Tschetschenien zugebracht.\"</ref> in Duba-yurt and [[Grozny]].<ref name=LOB01>[[Peter Pomerantsev|Pomerantsev, Peter]]. [http://www.lrb.co.uk/v33/n20/peter-pomerantsev/putins-rasputin 'Putin's Rasputin']. ''[[London Review of Books]]''. 33 (20). 20 October 2011. pp. 3\u20136.</ref><ref>[http://www.inosmi.ru/translation/220396.html '\u0412\u043b\u0430\u0434\u0438\u0441\u043b\u0430\u0432 \u0421\u0443\u0440\u043a\u043e\u0432: \"\u0417\u0430\u043f\u0430\u0434 \u043d\u0435 \u043e\u0431\u044f\u0437\u0430\u043d \u043d\u0430\u0441 \u043b\u044e\u0431\u0438\u0442\u044c\",'] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20050831170152/http://www.inosmi.ru/translation/220396.html |date=31 August 2005 }} in Inopressa Newsagency. 20 June 2005.</ref> Surkov is reportedly a relative of [[Dzhokhar Dudayev]], the first [[President of the Chechen Republic of Ichkeria]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.themoscowtimes.com/2013/09/22/surkov-makes-kremlin-comeback-a27890|title=Surkov Makes Kremlin Comeback|newspaper=The Moscow Times|date=22 September 2013|access-date=10 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nFrom 1982 to 1983, Surkov attended [[National University of Science and Technology MISiS (Russia)|MISiS]], but did not graduate from it. From 1983 to 1985, Surkov served in a Soviet artillery regiment in [[Hungary]], according to his official biography.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.opendemocracy.net/od-russia/richard-sakwa/surkov-dark-prince-of-kremlin|title=Surkov: dark prince of the Kremlin|last=Sakwa|first=Richard|date=7 April 2011|website=[[openDemocracy]]|publisher=|access-date=20 November 2016}}</ref> However, former [[Defence Minister]] [[Sergei Ivanov]] stated in a 2006 TV interview that Surkov served in the [[GRU|Main Intelligence Directorate of the General Staff]] (GRU) during the same time period.<ref name=\"lenta.ru\">[http://lenta.ru/lib/14159273/full.htm ''\u0421\u0443\u0440\u043a\u043e\u0432, \u0412\u043b\u0430\u0434\u0438\u0441\u043b\u0430\u0432'']. lenta.ru</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://perebezhchik.ru/person/surkov-vladislav--yurevich/|title=\u0421\u0443\u0440\u043a\u043e\u0432 \u0412\u043b\u0430\u0434\u0438\u0441\u043b\u0430\u0432 \u042e\u0440\u044c\u0435\u0432\u0438\u0447 \u2013 \u0434\u043e\u0441\u044c\u0435, \u0432\u0441\u0435 \u043d\u043e\u0432\u043e\u0441\u0442\u0438|last=|first=|date=|work=|newspaper=\u041f\u0435\u0440\u0435\u0431\u0435\u0436\u0447\u0438\u043a|trans-title=Vladislav, Surkov Yurevich \u2013 dossier and news|quote=According to one information source, he served in the artillery of the Southern Group of Forces in Hungary. According to another, he served in the special forces of the Main Intelligence Directorate (GRU). (\u041f\u043e \u043e\u0434\u043d\u043e\u0439 \u0438\u043d\u0444\u043e\u0440\u043c\u0430\u0446\u0438\u0438, \u0441\u043b\u0443\u0436\u0431\u0443 \u043e\u043d \u043f\u0440\u043e\u0445\u043e\u0434\u0438\u043b \u0432 \u0430\u0440\u0442\u0438\u043b\u043b\u0435\u0440\u0438\u0439\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0439 \u0447\u0430\u0441\u0442\u0438 \u042e\u0436\u043d\u043e\u0439 \u0433\u0440\u0443\u043f\u043f\u044b \u0432\u043e\u0439\u0441\u043a \u0432 \u0412\u0435\u043d\u0433\u0440\u0438\u0438. \u041f\u043e \u0434\u0440\u0443\u0433\u043e\u0439 \u2013 \u0432 \u0441\u043f\u0435\u0446\u043d\u0430\u0437\u0435 \u0413\u043b\u0430\u0432\u043d\u043e\u0433\u043e \u0440\u0430\u0437\u0432\u0435\u0434\u044b\u0432\u0430\u0442\u0435\u043b\u044c\u043d\u043e\u0433\u043e \u0443\u043f\u0440\u0430\u0432\u043b\u0435\u043d\u0438\u044f (\u0413\u0420\u0423).)|access-date=20 November 2016|via=}}</ref>\n\nAfter his military training, Surkov was accepted{{when|date=March 2015}} to [[Moscow Institute of Culture]] for a five-year program in theater direction, but spent only three years there.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.themoscowtimes.com/people/article/vladislav_surkov/433802.html|title=Vladislav Surkov Biography|date=25 March 2011|publisher=[[The Moscow Times]]|access-date=20 November 2016|url-status=bot: unknown|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140902152411/http://www.themoscowtimes.com/people/article/vladislav_surkov/433802.html|archivedate=2 September 2014|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Surkov graduated from [[Moscow International University]] with a master's degree in economics in the late 1990s.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n==Business career (1988\u20131998)==\nIn the late 1980s, when the government lifted the ban against private businesses, Surkov started out in business. In 1987, he became head of the advertising department of [[Mikhail Khodorkovsky]]'s businesses. From 1991 to April 1996, he held key managerial positions in advertising and PR departments of Khodorkovsky's [[Bank Menatep]]. From March 1996 to February 1997, he was at Rosprom, and since February 1997 with [[Mikhail Fridman]]'s [[Alfa-Bank]].<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nIn September 2004, Surkov was elected president of the board of directors of the oil products transportation company [[Transnefteproduct]], but was instructed by Russia's prime minister [[Mikhail Fradkov]] to give up the position in February 2006.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.kommersant.ru/doc/649226|title=\u0412\u043b\u0430\u0434\u0438\u0441\u043b\u0430\u0432 \u0421\u0443\u0440\u043a\u043e\u0432 \u043f\u043e\u043a\u0438\u043d\u0435\u0442 \"\u0422\u0440\u0430\u043d\u0441\u043d\u0435\u0444\u0442\u0435\u043f\u0440\u043e\u0434\u0443\u043a\u0442\"|last=|first=|date=13 February 2006|work=|newspaper=\u041a\u043e\u043c\u043c\u0435\u0440\u0441\u0430\u043d\u0442\u044a ([[Kommersant]])|issue=25|pages=13|language=Russian|trans-title=Vladislav Surkov leaves \"Transnefteprodukt\"|quote=By an order signed by Prime Minister [[Mikhail Fradkov]], the Board of Directors of \"Transnefteprodukt\", Deputy of the Presidential Executive Office Vladislav Surkov, resigns. (\u041f\u043e \u043f\u043e\u0434\u043f\u0438\u0441\u0430\u043d\u043d\u043e\u043c\u0443 \u043f\u0440\u0435\u043c\u044c\u0435\u0440\u043e\u043c \u041c\u0438\u0445\u0430\u0438\u043b\u043e\u043c \u0424\u0440\u0430\u0434\u043a\u043e\u0432\u044b\u043c \u0440\u0430\u0441\u043f\u043e\u0440\u044f\u0436\u0435\u043d\u0438\u044e, \u0441\u043e\u0432\u0435\u0442 \u0434\u0438\u0440\u0435\u043a\u0442\u043e\u0440\u043e\u0432 \u041e\u0410\u041e \"\u0422\u0440\u0430\u043d\u0441\u043d\u0435\u0444\u0442\u0435\u043f\u0440\u043e\u0434\u0443\u043a\u0442\" \u043f\u043e\u043a\u0438\u043d\u0435\u0442 \u0432\u043e\u0437\u0433\u043b\u0430\u0432\u043b\u044f\u0432\u0448\u0438\u0439 \u0435\u0433\u043e \u0437\u0430\u043c\u0435\u0441\u0442\u0438\u0442\u0435\u043b\u044c \u0440\u0443\u043a\u043e\u0432\u043e\u0434\u0438\u0442\u0435\u043b\u044f \u0430\u0434\u043c\u0438\u043d\u0438\u0441\u0442\u0440\u0430\u0446\u0438\u0438 \u043f\u0440\u0435\u0437\u0438\u0434\u0435\u043d\u0442\u0430 \u0420\u0424 \u0412\u043b\u0430\u0434\u0438\u0441\u043b\u0430\u0432 \u0421\u0443\u0440\u043a\u043e\u0432.)|access-date=20 November 2016|via=}}</ref>\n\n==Political career (1999\u2013)==\n\n===Deputy Chief of the Russian Presidential Administration 1999\u20132011===\nAfter a brief career as a director for public relations on the Russian television [[Channel One (Russia)|ORT]] channel from 1998 to 1999, Surkov was appointed Deputy Chief of [[Russian presidential administration|Staff]] of the President of the Russian Federation in 1999.<ref name=Storey>{{cite web | last = Storey | first = Peter | title = Vladislav Surkov: The (Gray) Cardinal of the Kremlin | url = http://ciceromagazine.com/features/the-gray-cardinal-of-the-kremlin/ | work = [[Cicero (magazine)|Cicero]] | date = 17 June 2015 | accessdate = 9 November 2015}}</ref>\n\nDuring the beginning of his time in this role, Surkov's main appearances in public and in international media were as a [[public relations]] mouthpiece of the Kremlin. In August 2000, he confirmed that [[Gazprom]] would buy [[Vladimir Gusinsky]]'s [[Gazprom-Media|Media-Most]], which at the time owned the only independent, nationwide Russian television channel, [[NTV (Russia)|NTV]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/image/120736880/?terms=Vladislav%2BSurkov|title=Kremlin closing in on media network|last=|first=|date=4 August 2008|work=[[The Sydney Morning Herald]]|access-date=|via=Newspapers.com}}</ref> In September 2002, he stated on behalf of the Kremlin that they had decided not to return the statue of [[KGB]] founder [[Felix Dzerzhinsky]] that had been torn down during [[Dissolution of the Soviet Union|the fall of the Soviet Union]] in 1991.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/image/202201676/?terms=Vladislav%2BSurkov|title=Return of statue opposed|last=Gutterman|first=Steve|date=20 September 2002|work=[[Statesman Journal]] via [[Associated Press]]|page=7A|access-date=|via=Newspapers.com}}</ref> After the [[2003 Russian legislative election|2003 Russian Duma elections]], when the president's [[United Russia|United Russia party]] got the most [[State Duma|seats]] at 37.6%, Surkov delivered the Kremlin's enthusiastic response, saying \"We are living in a new Russia now.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://articles.latimes.com/2003/dec/09/world/fg-putin9|title=The Victor Extends an Olive Branch|last=Holley|first=David|date=9 December 2003|newspaper=Los Angeles Times|language=en-US|issn=0458-3035|access-date=23 November 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2004, he was additionally appointed as aide to the president.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://polit.ru/news/2015/09/21/surkov/|title=\u041c\u0435\u043c\u043e\u0440\u0438\u044f. \u0412\u043b\u0430\u0434\u0438\u0441\u043b\u0430\u0432 \u0421\u0443\u0440\u043a\u043e\u0432|last=|first=|date=21 September 2015|website= polit.ru|publisher=|language=Russian|trans-title=Vladislav Surkov fact sheet|access-date=20 November 2016}}</ref>\n\nSince 2006, Surkov has advocated a political doctrine he has called [[sovereign democracy]], to counter democracy promotion conducted by the USA and European states.<ref>[http://www.cdi.org/russia/johnson/2006-212-37.cfm] title? cdi.org. 2006.</ref> Judged by some Western media as controversial, this view has not generally been shared by Russian media and the Russian political elite.<ref name=\"roundtable\">[http://www.izvestia.ru/politic/article3096139/?print On Wednesday Political Elite Agreed to Speak Common Language]. \u00abIzvestia\u00bb. 31 August 2006.</ref> Surkov sees this concept as a national version of the common political language that will be used when Russia talks to the outside world.<ref name=\"roundtable\"/> As the most influential ideologist of \"sovereign democracy\", Surkov gave two programmatic speeches in 2006: \"Sovereignty is a Political Synonym of Competitiveness\" in February<ref>[http://www.edinros.ru/news.html?id=111148 Sovereignty is a Political Synonym of Competitiveness] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20061208020210/http://www.edinros.ru/news.html?id=111148 |date=8 December 2006 }}. Vladislav Surkov, public appearance. 7 February 2006.</ref> and \"Our Russian Model of Democracy is Titled Sovereign Democracy\" in June 2006.<ref>[http://www.edinros.ru/news.html?id=114108 Our Russian Model of Democracy is Titled \u00abSovereign Democracy\u00bb] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20061105125847/http://www.edinros.ru/news.html?id=114108 |date=5 November 2006 }}. Vladislav Surkov, briefing. 28 June 2006. edinros.ru.</ref>\n[[File:Vladislav Surkov in 2010.jpeg|thumb|left|Vladislav Surkov in April 2010]]\n\nOn 8 February 2007, [[Moscow State University]] marked the 125th anniversary of U.S. President [[Franklin D. Roosevelt]]'s birth with a high-level conference \"Lessons of the [[New Deal]] for Modern Russia and the World\" attended, among others, by Surkov and [[Gleb Pavlovsky]]. Surkov drew an explicit parallel between Roosevelt and Russian president Putin, praising the legacy of Roosevelt's New Deal, and between the US of the 1930s and present-day Russia. Pavlovsky called on Putin to follow Roosevelt in staying for a third presidential term.<ref>[http://www.kommersant.com/p741228/Putin_Roosevelt_Third_Term/ \u0412\u043b\u0430\u0434\u0438\u043c\u0438\u0440 \u0412\u043b\u0430\u0434\u0438\u043c\u0438\u0440\u043e\u0432\u0438\u0447 \u0420\u0443\u0437\u0432\u0435\u043b\u044c\u0442/ Putin Asked to Follow FDR's Example]. ''[[Kommersant]]''. 9 February 2007.</ref><ref>[http://www.mosnews.com/news/2007/02/09/putinroosvelt.shtml Kremlin Official Compares Putin to Franklin D. Roosevelt]. [[Moscow News]]. 9 February 2007.</ref><ref>[http://en.rian.ru/russia/20070208/60427066.html Roosevelt Russia's ideological ally \u2013 Putin aide]. [[RIA Novosti]]. 8 February 2007.</ref>\n\nAccording to ''[[The Moscow Times]]'', Surkov exerted his influence to have [[Ramzan Kadyrov]] appointed as acting [[Head of the Chechen Republic]] on 15 February 2007.<ref name=\":5\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.forbes.ru/sobytiya-photogallery/vlast/238819-put-surkova-ot-ohrannika-do-vitse-premera/photo/11|title=\u0421\u0443\u0440\u043a\u043e\u0432 \u0438 \u041a\u0430\u0434\u044b\u0440\u043e\u0432|last=13 May 2013|first=|date=|website=www.forbes.ru|publisher=[[Forbes]] Russia|trans-title=Surkov and Kadyrov|access-date=20 November 2016}}</ref> Since this appointment, Kadyrov has gone on to serve two terms in office and has been accused of numerous humans rights abuses.<ref>See [[Ramzan Kadyrov#Accusations of human rights abuses|Ramzan Kadyrov \u00a7\u00a7 Accusations of human rights abuses]]</ref>\n\nIn October 2009, Surkov warned that opening and modernization of Russia's political system, a need repeatedly stressed by President [[Dmitry Medvedev]], could result in more instability, which \"could rip Russia apart\".<ref>Sirke M\u00e4kinen, \"Surkovian narrative on the future of Russia: making Russia a world leader.\" ''Journal of Communist Studies and Transition Politics'' 27#2 (2011): 143\u2013165.</ref>\n\nIn September 2011, [[Mikhail Prokhorov]] quit the [[Party of Growth|Right Cause party]], which he had led for five months. He condemned the party as a puppet of the Kremlin and named Surkov the \"main puppet master of the political process\" ({{Lang-ru|\u0433\u043b\u0430\u0432\u043d\u044b\u043c \u043a\u0443\u043a\u043b\u043e\u0432\u043e\u0434\u043e\u043c \u043f\u043e\u043b\u0438\u0442\u0438\u0447\u0435\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0433\u043e \u043f\u0440\u043e\u0446\u0435\u0441\u0441\u0430|link=no}}), according to a report in Russian-language magazine ''[[Korrespondent]]'' picked up by ''The New York Times''.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://korrespondent.net/russia/1261740-prohorov-nazval-glavnogo-kuklovoda-politicheskogo-processa-v-rossii|title=\u041f\u0440\u043e\u0445\u043e\u0440\u043e\u0432 \u043d\u0430\u0437\u0432\u0430\u043b  \u0433\u043b\u0430\u0432\u043d\u043e\u0433\u043e \u043a\u0443\u043a\u043b\u043e\u0432\u043e\u0434\u0430 \u043f\u043e\u043b\u0438\u0442\u0438\u0447\u0435\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0433\u043e \u043f\u0440\u043e\u0446\u0435\u0441\u0441\u0430 \u0432 \u0420\u043e\u0441\u0441\u0438\u0438|last=|first=|date=15 September 2011|work=[[Korrespondent]]|language=Russian|access-date=20 November 2016|via=}}</ref><ref>Kramer, Andrew E., and Ellen Barry, [https://www.nytimes.com/2011/09/16/world/europe/amid-political-rancor-russian-party-leader-mikhail-prokhorov-quits.html?hp \"Amid Political Rancor, Russian Party Leader Quits\"]. ''The New York Times''. 15 September 2011. Retrieved 15 September 2011.</ref> Prokhorov had hoped that Surkov would be fired from the Kremlin, but the Kremlin stood behind Surkov and said he would not disappear from the political stage.<ref>Volkskrant. 16 September 2011.</ref> At that time, ''[[Reuters]]'' described Surkov in a profile as the Kremlin's 'shadowy chief political strategist', one of the most powerful men in the Kremlin and considered a close ally of then-Prime Minister Putin.<ref name=RE01/>\n\n===Deputy Prime Minister for Economic Modernisation 2011\u20132013===\nOn 28 December 2011, Medvedev reassigned Surkov to the role of \"Deputy Prime Minister for Economic Modernisation\" in a move interpreted by many to be fallout from the controversial [[2011 Russian legislative election|Russian parliamentary elections of 2011]].<ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/world/2011/dec/27/vladimir-putin-ejects-vladislav-surkov \"Putin ejects Kremlin 'puppet master' after protests\"]. Associated Press via ''The Guardian''. 27 December 2011.</ref> At that time, Surkov described his past career as follows:<ref>[http://rbth.ru/articles/2011/12/28/the_gray_cardinal_leaves_the_kremlin_14123.html The gray cardinal leaves the Kremlin]. ''Russia Beyond the Headlines''. 28 December 2011.</ref> \"I was among those who helped [[Boris Yeltsin]] to secure a peaceful transfer of power; among those who helped President Putin stabilize the political system; among those who helped President Medvedev liberalize it. All the teams were great.\"\n\n[[File:\u0412\u043b\u0430\u0434\u0438\u0441\u043b\u0430\u0432 \u0421\u0443\u0440\u043a\u043e\u0432 \u043d\u0430 V \u0441\u044a\u0435\u0437\u0434\u0435 \u041d\u0410\u0428\u0418\u0445.JPG|thumb|Surkov giving a speech during the Fifth Congress of the Nashi Youth Movement]]\nDuring this time, Surkov helped create some pro-government youth movements, including [[Nashi (youth movement)|Nashi]]. He met with their leaders and participants several times and gave them lectures on the political situation.<ref>[http://www.ncsj.org/AuxPages/030205RFERL_Putin.shtml] ncsj.org  {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070124171111/http://www.ncsj.org/AuxPages/030205RFERL_Putin.shtml|date=24 January 2007}}</ref><ref>Maya Atwal and Edwin Bacon. \"The youth movement Nashi: contentious politics, civil society, and party politics.\" ''East European Politics'' 28.3 (2012): 256\u2013266.</ref> Nashi has been compared by [[Edward Lucas (journalist)|Edward Lucas]] as the Putin government's version of the Soviet-era [[Komsomol]].<ref>{{cite book|url=|title=The new cold war: Putin's Russia and the threat to the West|last=Lucas|first=Edward|publisher=St. Martin's Press|year=2014|isbn=9781137472618|edition=3rd|location=New York|pages=102\u2013105|quote=|via=}}{{rp|page=102}}\n</ref>[[File:Sergey Ivanov, Vladislav Surkov and Arkady Dvorkovich 7 May 2013.jpeg|thumb|Surkov on his last day as Deputy Prime Minister in a meeting with [[Sergei Ivanov|Sergey Ivanov]] ([[Kremlin Chief of Staff|Chief of Presidential Staff]]) and his ministerial colleague [[Arkady Dvorkovich]]]]\n\nSince Putin's return to the presidency in 2012, Surkov became marginalized as Putin \"pursued a path of open repression over the cunning manipulation favoured by Surkov\". As a Deputy Prime Minister, Surkov criticized the Kremlin's Investigative Committee, which led investigations into opposition leaders, rather than the general prosecutor's office. The Committee stated he offered to resign on 7 May 2013, whereas Surkov stated he offered to resign on 28 April 2013. Putin signed it on 8 May 2013.<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20130622185409/http://government.ru/persons/171/ ''\u0421\u0443\u0440\u043a\u043e\u0432 \u0412\u043b\u0430\u0434\u0438\u0441\u043b\u0430\u0432 \u042e\u0440\u044c\u0435\u0432\u0438\u0447'']. government.ru. 22 June 2013.</ref><ref>Miriam Elder: [https://www.theguardian.com/world/2013/may/08/vladimir-putin-cardinal-forced-government ''Vladimir Putin's former 'cardinal' forced out of government'']. The Guardian. 8 May 2013.</ref>\n\n===Personal advisor to Putin, 2013\u20132020===\n[[File:Normandy format talks 2016-10-19.jpg|thumb|The \"[[Normandy Format]]\" talks in 2016 where Surkov sits between [[Vladimir Putin]] and [[Frank-Walter Steinmeier]]]]\n[[File:Normandy format (2019-10-09) 03.jpg|thumb|The \"[[Normandy Format]]\" talks in 2019 where Surkov sits aside with [[Sergei Lavrov]]]]\nDuring Putin's first two terms as president, Surkov was regarded as the Kremlin's \"grey cardinal\", due to crafting Russia's system of \"sovereign democracy\" and directing its propaganda principally through control of state run television.<ref>Anna Nemtsova, Eli Lake: [http://www.thedailybeast.com/articles/2014/03/19/obama-targets-the-mastermind-behind-putin-s-power-play.html ''Is This the Mastermind Behind Russia's Crimea Grab?''] The Daily Beast. 19 March 2014</ref> On 20 September 2013, Vladimir Putin appointed Surkov as his Aide in the [[Presidential Administration of Russia|Presidential Executive Office]].<ref name=\"kremlinbio\" /> He also became Putin's personal adviser on relationships with [[Abkhazia]], [[South Ossetia]] and [[Ukraine]].<ref name=\"forbes.ua\"/><ref name=tass/>\n \nOn 17 March 2014, the day after the [[2014 Crimean referendum|Crimean status referendum]], Surkov became one of the first eleven persons who were placed under executive sanctions on the [[Office of Foreign Assets Control#Specially Designated Nationals List|Specially Designated Nationals List (SDN)]] by President [[Barack Obama]], freezing his assets in the US and banning him from entering the United States.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.businessinsider.com/crimea-vote-referendum-sanctions-obama-putin-2014-3|title=Obama Just Announced Sanctions Against 7 Russian 'Cronies'|journal=[[Business Insider]] |first=Brett| last=Logiurato| date=17 March 2014|accessdate=17 March 2014}}</ref><ref name=StateUkraineRussiaSanctions>{{cite web | title = Ukraine and Russia Sanctions | url = https://2009-2017.state.gov/e/eb/tfs/spi/ukrainerussia | publisher = United States State Department | accessdate = 4 March 2016}}</ref><ref name=FirstListWhiteHouse>{{cite web | title = Fact Sheet: Ukraine-Related Sanctions | url = https://www.whitehouse.gov/the-press-office/2014/03/17/fact-sheet-ukraine-related-sanctions | publisher = The White House: Office of the Press Secretary | date = 17 March 2014 | accessdate = 4 March 2016}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web | title = Executive Order \u2013 Blocking Property of Additional Persons Contributing to the Situation in Ukraine | url = http://www.whitehouse.gov/the-press-office/2014/03/20/executive-order-blocking-property-additional-persons-contributing-situat | publisher = The White House: Office of the Press Secretary | date = 20 March 2014 | accessdate = 4 March 2016}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|title=Treasury Sanctions Russian Officials, Members Of The Russian Leadership's Inner Circle, And An Entity For Involvement In The Situation In Ukraine |url=http://www.treasury.gov/press-center/press-releases/Pages/jl23331.aspx |publisher=United States Department of the Treasury}}</ref><ref name=TreasurySanctionsUkraineFirstList>{{cite web | title = Issuance of a new Ukraine-related Executive Order; Ukraine-related Designations  | url = https://www.treasury.gov/resource-center/sanctions/OFAC-Enforcement/Pages/20140317.aspx | publisher = United States Department of the Treasury | date = 17 March 2014 | accessdate = 4 March 2016}}</ref><ref name=TreasurySanctionsUkraineSecondList>{{cite web | title = Ukraine-related Designations | url = https://www.treasury.gov/resource-center/sanctions/OFAC-Enforcement/Pages/20140320_33.aspx | publisher = United States Department of the Treasury | date = 20 March 2014 | accessdate = 4 March 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | title = Specially Designated Nationals List (SDN) | url = http://www.treasury.gov/resource-center/sanctions/SDN-List/Pages/default.aspx | publisher = United States Department of the Treasury}}</ref><ref name=Sanctions>{{cite web | last = Shuklin | first = Peter | title = Putin's inner circle: who got in a new list of US sanctions | url = https://news.liga.net/articles/politics/1066761-blizhniy_krug_putina_kto_popal_v_novyy_spisok_sanktsiy_ssha.htm | publisher = liga.net | date = 21 March 2014 | accessdate = 20 February 2016 | url-status = dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20150207152258/http://news.liga.net/articles/politics/1066761-blizhniy_krug_putina_kto_popal_v_novyy_spisok_sanktsiy_ssha.htm | archivedate = 7 February 2015 | df = dmy-all }}</ref><ref name=Ukraine-EO13660>{{cite web | last = President of The United States | title = Ukraine EO13660 | url = https://www.treasury.gov/resource-center/sanctions/Programs/Documents/ukraine_eo.pdf | publisher = Federal Register | date = 10 March 2014 | accessdate = 4 March 2016}}</ref><ref name=Ukraine-EO13661>{{cite web | last = President of The United States | title = Ukraine EO13661 | url = https://www.treasury.gov/resource-center/sanctions/Programs/Documents/ukraine_eo2.pdf | publisher = Federal Register | date = 19 March 2014 | accessdate = 20 February 2016}}</ref>{{efn|The individuals on the first list of United States sanctions for individuals or entities involved in the Ukraine crisis are Sergey Aksyonov, Sergey Glazyev, Andrei Klishas, Vladimir Konstantinov, Valentina Matviyenko, Victor Medvedchuk, Yelena Mizulina, Dmitry Rogozin, Leonid Slutsky, Vladislav Surkov, and Victor Yakunovich.<ref name=FirstListWhiteHouse/><ref name=TreasurySanctionsUkraineFirstList/>}} Surkov responded to this by saying: \"The only things that interest me in the US are [[Tupac Shakur]], [[Allen Ginsberg]], and [[Jackson Pollock]]. I don\u2019t need a visa to access their work.\"<ref>[https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/europe/vladimir-putins-top-aide-vladislav-surkov-mocks-us-sanctions-the-only-thing-that-interests-me-about-9200170.html Vladimir Putin's top aide Vladislav Surkov mocks US sanctions]. ''[[The Independent]]''. 18 March 2014.</ref>\n\nOn 21 March 2014, the European Union (EU) placed Surkov on its [[List of individuals sanctioned during the Ukrainian crisis|sanction list]] barring him from entering the EU and freezing his assets in the EU.<ref name=\"EU-sanctions-21March\">{{cite web|url=http://eur-lex.europa.eu/legal-content/EN/TXT/?qid=1457224758727&uri=CELEX:32014R0284|title=Council Implementing Regulation (EU) No 284/2014 of 21 March 2014 implementing Regulation (EU) No 269/2014 concerning restrictive measures in respect of actions undermining or threatening the territorial integrity, sovereignty and independence of Ukraine (EUR-Lex \u2013 32014R0284 \u2013 EN)|work=EUR-Lex|date=21 March 2014}}</ref><ref name=BBC19Dec2014>{{cite web | title = Ukraine crisis: Russia and sanctions | url = https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-26672800 | publisher = BBC | date = 19 December 2014 | accessdate = 4 March 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2015, Ukrainian authorities accused Surkov of organizing snipers to kill protesters and police during the Ukrainian [[Euromaidan]] in January 2014.<ref>[https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-31548896 ''Ukraine accuses Russia over Maidan 2014 killings'']. bbc.com. 20 February 2015.</ref><ref>[http://www.pravda.com.ua/articles/2015/05/12/7067579/ ''Nemtsov Report: Putin. War'']. [[Ukrayinska Pravda]]. 12 May 2015.</ref><ref>[http://www.belsat.eu/en/articles/putins-aide-surkov-pulled-strings-snipers-shot-maidan-protesters-ukraines-sbu/ ''Putin's aide Surkov pulled the strings as snipers shot at Maidan protesters \u2013 Ukraine's SBU'']. belsat.eu. 20 February 2015. According to SBU director Nalyvaichenko, they have identified some of the shooters and \"as part of this case we have job titles, last names, copies of passports, dates of their entry and departure, their telephone providers and places of accommodation, [we know] how president Putin's adviser Surkov was coordinating their actions in Kyiv,\"</ref> This accusation was dismissed by the Russian government as \"absurd\".<ref name=tass>[http://tass.ru/en/russia/778994 ''Kiev's allegations that Surkov was behind Maidan developments in 2014 absurd \u2014 ForMin'']. [[Russian News Agency TASS|tass.ru]]. 20 February 2015.</ref>\n\nDespite being barred from entering the EU, Surkov visited Greece's [[Mount Athos]] as a part of Putin's delegation to the holy site in May 2016.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Shuster|first1=Simon|title=Exclusive: Putin Aide Vladislav Surkov Defied E.U. Sanctions to Make Pilgrimage to Greece|url=http://time.com/4476005/vladislav-surkov-putin-athos-greece-sanctions/|work=Time|date=2 September 2016}}</ref>\n\nOn 11 February 2019, Surkov published in the [[Nezavisimaya Gazeta]] article \u201cThe Long State of Putin\u201d, which describes the main points of the term \u201c[[Putinism]]\u201d proposed by him.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ng.ru/ideas/2019-02-11/5_7503_surkov.html|title=\u0412\u043b\u0430\u0434\u0438\u0441\u043b\u0430\u0432 \u0421\u0443\u0440\u043a\u043e\u0432: \u0414\u043e\u043b\u0433\u043e\u0435 \u0433\u043e\u0441\u0443\u0434\u0430\u0440\u0441\u0442\u0432\u043e \u041f\u0443\u0442\u0438\u043d\u0430|website=www.ng.ru|language=en|access-date=17 October 2019}}</ref> The article caused a stir in the media.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.helsinki.fi/en/news/society-economy/surkov-and-the-three-pillars-of-putinism|title=Surkov and the three pillars of Putinism|date=24 April 2019|website=University of Helsinki|language=en|access-date=17 October 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2019/mar/25/russian-meddling-vladimir-putin-vladislav-surkov|title=The confusion around Russian \u2018meddling\u2019 means they\u2019re already winning {{!}} Gabriel Gatehouse|last=Gatehouse|first=Gabriel|date=25 March 2019|work=The Guardian|access-date=17 October 2019|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/europe/putin-russia-kremlin-vladislav-surkov-grey-cardinal-moscow-a8773661.html|title=Putin advisor says 'Russia is playing with the West's minds'|date=12 February 2019|website=The Independent|language=en|access-date=17 October 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2020, Surkov was removed from his role of advisor.<ref name=\":8\" /> On 26 February 2020, he gave an interview to ''Aktualnyie kommentarii'' where he stated that he actually resigned from the post on his own initiative and the reasons were correctly disclosed by Russian journalists [[Vladimir Solovyov (journalist)|Vladimir Solovyev]]<ref>[https://www.kommersant.ru/doc/4233004 \u0414\u043c\u0438\u0442\u0440\u0438\u0439 \u041a\u043e\u0437\u0430\u043a \u0441\u043e\u0431\u0438\u0440\u0430\u0435\u0442\u0441\u044f \u0432 \u043d\u043e\u0432\u044b\u0439 \u043f\u043e\u0434\u0445\u043e\u0434 \u043d\u0430 \u0423\u043a\u0440\u0430\u0438\u043d\u0443]. ''Kommersant''.</ref> and [[Alexei Venediktov]].<ref name=actualcomment200226>{{cite web|url=http://actualcomment.ru/surkov-mne-interesno-deystvovat-protiv-realnosti-2002260855.html|title=Surkov: I am interested to act against the reality|website=Actualcomment.ru|last=Chesnakov|first=Aleksei|date=26 February 2020|language=ru|trans-title=\u0421\u0443\u0440\u043a\u043e\u0432: \u043c\u043d\u0435 \u0438\u043d\u0442\u0435\u0440\u0435\u0441\u043d\u043e \u0434\u0435\u0439\u0441\u0442\u0432\u043e\u0432\u0430\u0442\u044c \u043f\u0440\u043e\u0442\u0438\u0432 \u0440\u0435\u0430\u043b\u044c\u043d\u043e\u0441\u0442\u0438|quote=\u041f\u0440\u0438\u043d\u0443\u0436\u0434\u0435\u043d\u0438\u0435 \u0441\u0438\u043b\u043e\u0439 \u043a \u0431\u0440\u0430\u0442\u0441\u043a\u0438\u043c \u043e\u0442\u043d\u043e\u0448\u0435\u043d\u0438\u044f\u043c \u2014 \u0435\u0434\u0438\u043d\u0441\u0442\u0432\u0435\u043d\u043d\u044b\u0439 \u043c\u0435\u0442\u043e\u0434, \u0438\u0441\u0442\u043e\u0440\u0438\u0447\u0435\u0441\u043a\u0438 \u0434\u043e\u043a\u0430\u0437\u0430\u0432\u0448\u0438\u0439 \u044d\u0444\u0444\u0435\u043a\u0442\u0438\u0432\u043d\u043e\u0441\u0442\u044c \u043d\u0430 \u0443\u043a\u0440\u0430\u0438\u043d\u0441\u043a\u043e\u043c \u043d\u0430\u043f\u0440\u0430\u0432\u043b\u0435\u043d\u0438\u0438. \u041d\u0435 \u0434\u0443\u043c\u0430\u044e, \u0447\u0442\u043e \u0431\u0443\u0434\u0435\u0442 \u0438\u0437\u043e\u0431\u0440\u0435\u0442\u0435\u043d \u043a\u0430\u043a\u043e\u0439-\u0442\u043e \u0434\u0440\u0443\u0433\u043e\u0439.}}</ref> Surkov added that he was primarily involved with Donbass and Ukraine, but since the \"context\" has changed he decided to leave.<ref name=actualcomment200226/> He also explained that \"coercion to fraternal relations by force is the only method that has historically proven its effectiveness in the Ukrainian direction. I do not think that some other will be invented\".<ref name=actualcomment200226/>\n\n====Hacked emails====\n{{main|Surkov leaks}}\nIn October 2016, Ukrainian hacker group CyberHunta released over a gigabyte of emails and other documents alleged to belong to Surkov.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Windrem|first1=Robert|title=Payback? Russia gets hacked, revealing top Putin aide's secrets|url=http://www.nbcnews.com/storyline/ukraine-crisis/payback-russia-gets-hacked-revealing-putin-aide-s-secrets-n673956|work=NBC News|date=27 October 2016}}</ref> The 2,337 emails belonged to the inbox of Surkov's office email account, prm_surkova@gov.ru.<ref name=\"DFRL\">{{cite web|author1=Digital Forensic Research Lab|title=Breaking Down the Surkov Leaks \u2013 DFRLab|url=https://medium.com/dfrlab/breaking-down-the-surkov-leaks-b2feec1423cb#.t4wz7vsnx|website=Medium|publisher=Atlantic Council|date=25 October 2016}}</ref> The Kremlin suggested that the leaked documents were fake.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Walker|first1=Shaun|title=Kremlin puppet master's leaked emails are price of return to political frontline|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2016/oct/26/kremlin-puppet-masters-leaked-emails-vladislav-surkov-east-ukraine|work=The Guardian|date=26 October 2016}}</ref>\n\nThe emails illustrate Russian plans to politically destabilize Ukraine and the coordination of affairs with major opposition leaders in separatist east Ukraine.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Murdock|first1=Jason|title=Surkov leaks: Thousands of hacked emails reportedly from high-ranking Kremlin official published|url=http://www.ibtimes.co.uk/surkov-leaks-thousands-hacked-emails-high-ranking-kremlin-officials-published-1588645|work=International Business Times UK|date=27 October 2016}}</ref> The document release included a document sent by [[Denis Pushilin]], former Chair of the [[People's Soviet of the Donetsk People's Republic|People's Soviet]] of the [[Donetsk People's Republic]], listing casualties that occurred from 26 May to\u200a 6 June 2014.<ref name=\"DFRL\"/> It also included a 22-page outline of \"a plan to support nationalist and separatist politicians and to encourage early parliamentary elections in Ukraine, all with the aim of undermining the government in Kiev.\"<ref>{{cite news|last1=Standish|first1=Reid|title=Hacked: Putin Aide's Emails Detail Alleged Plot to Destabilize Ukraine|url=https://foreignpolicy.com/2016/10/25/hacked-putin-aides-emails-detail-alleged-plot-to-destabilize-kiev-surkov-ukraine-leaks/|work=Foreign Policy|date=25 October 2016}}</ref>\n\n{{See also|Sergey Glazyev#Glazyev tapes}}\n\n== Criticism and depictions ==\nBefore the 2010 U.S.-Russia \"Civil Society to Civil Society\" (C2C) summit, a [[United States House of Representatives|U.S. House of Representatives]] representative for [[Florida|the state of Florida]]'s [[Florida's 27th congressional district|27th district]], [[Ileana Ros-Lehtinen]] ([[Republican Party (United States)|R]]), was the lead signatory of a written petition which called upon the [[Presidency of Barack Obama|Obama administration]] to suspend U.S. participation in the summit until Surkov was replaced as a delegate for the Russian side. In an interview with [[Radio Free Europe/Radio Liberty|Radio Free Europe]], Ros-Lehtinen explained that she objected to Surkov's attendance as she views him as \"one of the main propagators of [[Media freedom in Russia|limiting freedom of speech in Russia]], intimidating Russian journalists and representatives of [[Political parties in Russia|opposition political parties]]\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.rferl.org/a/today_on_svoboda/1952096.html|title=Controversy Over Civil Society Representative Appointment, Human Rights Lawyer Detained|last=|first=|date=8 February 2010|website=RadioFreeEurope/RadioLiberty|publisher=|access-date=20 November 2016}}</ref> However, the summit went ahead despite her objections.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ethicsrussia.org/index.php/what-we-do/activities-through-2011/projects-activities2/135-report-on-us-russia-c2c-summit-is-released|title=December 2010 Report on US-Russia C2C Summit is released|last=|first=|date=|website=www.ethicsrussia.org|publisher=Center for Business Ethics and Corporate Governance|access-date=20 November 2016}}</ref> A 2007 [[Open Source Center]] \"Media Aid\" document identifies the Russian ''ura.ru'' information website as reportedly having links to Surkov.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://fas.org/irp/dni/osc/russian-media.pdf |title=Source Descriptors of Key Russian Media |publisher=[[Open Source Center]] |date=6 December 2007 |access-date=22 April 2017 |page=15 |website=fas.org |quote=ura.ru [...] reportedly has links to Kremlin aide Surkov }}</ref>\n\nInside Russia, Surkov has drawn criticism from activists and opposition groups: In [[2010 in Russia|September 2010]], [[Lyudmila Alexeyeva]] appealed to then-president [[Dmitry Medvedev]] to dismiss him.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://kommersant.ru/doc/1554113|title=\u0423 \u043f\u0440\u0430\u0432\u043e\u0437\u0430\u0449\u0438\u0442\u043d\u0438\u043a\u043e\u0432 \u0433\u043e\u0442\u043e\u0432\u043e \u043f\u0440\u043e\u0448\u0435\u043d\u0438\u0435 \u043e\u0431 \u043e\u0442\u0441\u0442\u0430\u0432\u043a\u0435|last=\u0422\u0438\u0440\u043c\u0430\u0441\u0442\u044d|first=\u041c\u0430\u0440\u0438\u044f-\u041b\u0443\u0438\u0437\u0430|date=12 September 2010|work=|last2=\u0422\u0438\u0440\u043c\u0430\u0441\u0442\u044d|first2=\u041c\u0430\u0440\u0438\u044f-\u041b\u0443\u0438\u0437\u0430|newspaper=\u0413\u0430\u0437\u0435\u0442\u0430 \"\u041a\u043e\u043c\u043c\u0435\u0440\u0441\u0430\u043d\u0442\u044a\"|issue=228|pages=3|language=Russian|access-date=20 November 2016|via=}}</ref> Opposition leaders [[Boris Nemtsov]] ([[Solidarnost]]), [[Vladimir Milov]] ([[Democratic Choice of Russia|Democratic Choice]]), and [[Vladimir Ryzhkov]] ([[People's Freedom Party]]) jointly demanded his resignation over policies perceived to threaten freedom of the press and journalists in Russia.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.polit.ru/news/2010/11/09/Surkov/|title=\u0418\u0437\u0431\u0438\u0435\u043d\u0438\u0435 \u041a\u0430\u0448\u0438\u043d\u0430: \u043e\u043f\u043f\u043e\u0437\u0438\u0446\u0438\u043e\u043d\u0435\u0440\u044b \u041d\u0435\u043c\u0446\u043e\u0432, \u0420\u044b\u0436\u043a\u043e\u0432 \u0438 \u041c\u0438\u043b\u043e\u0432 \u043f\u043e\u0442\u0440\u0435\u0431\u043e\u0432\u0430\u043b\u0438 \u043e\u0442\u0441\u0442\u0430\u0432\u043a\u0438 \u0421\u0443\u0440\u043a\u043e\u0432\u0430 \u2013 \u041f\u041e\u041b\u0418\u0422.\u0420\u0423|website=www.polit.ru|access-date=20 November 2016}}</ref> [[Igor Strelkov (officer)|Igor Ivanovich Strelkov]], who played a key role in the [[Russian military intervention in Ukraine (2014\u2013present)|Russian military intervention in Ukraine]], referred to Surkov as a \"notorious\" person who \"focuses only on destruction...as in [[South Ossetia]] and other regions where he focused on [[looting]] rather than aide\" ({{Lang-ru|\u044d\u0442\u043e \u043b\u044e\u0434\u0438, \u043a\u043e\u0442\u043e\u0440\u044b\u0435 \u043d\u0430\u0446\u0435\u043b\u0435\u043d\u044b \u0442\u043e\u043b\u044c\u043a\u043e \u043d\u0430 \u0440\u0430\u0437\u0440\u0443\u0448\u0435\u043d\u0438\u0435...\u0432 \u042e\u0436\u043d\u043e\u0439 \u041e\u0441\u0435\u0442\u0438\u0438, \u0432 \u0434\u0440\u0443\u0433\u0438\u0445 \u0440\u0435\u0433\u0438\u043e\u043d\u0430\u0445, \u0432\u0435\u0437\u0434\u0435, \u0433\u0434\u0435 \u043e\u043d \u043d\u0430\u0445\u043e\u0434\u0438\u043b\u0441\u044f...\u0440\u0430\u0437\u0433\u0440\u0430\u0431\u043b\u0435\u043d\u0438\u0435\u043c \u0432\u043c\u0435\u0441\u0442\u043e \u0440\u0435\u0430\u043b\u044c\u043d\u043e\u0439 \u043f\u043e\u043c\u043e\u0449\u0438.|link=no}}).<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://novorossiia.ru/main/13879-g-n.html|title=\u042d\u043a\u0441\u043a\u043b\u044e\u0437\u0438\u0432\u043d\u043e\u0435 \u0438\u043d\u0442\u0435\u0440\u0432\u044c\u044e \u0418. \u0421\u0442\u0440\u0435\u043b\u043a\u043e\u0432\u0430: \"\u0421\u0440\u0430\u0436\u0430\u044f\u0441\u044c \u0437\u0430 \u041d\u043e\u0432\u043e\u0440\u043e\u0441\u0441\u0438\u044e, \u043c\u044b \u0441\u0440\u0430\u0436\u0430\u0435\u043c\u0441\u044f \u0437\u0430 \u0420\u043e\u0441\u0441\u0438\u044e\".|last=|first=|date=|website=novorossiia.ru|publisher=[[Novorossiya]]|access-date=20 November 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn 2013, Surkov was characterized by ''[[The Economist]]'' as the engineer of \"a system of make-believe\", \"a land of imitation political parties, stage-managed media and fake social movements\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.economist.com/news/europe/21577421-what-departure-vladislav-surkov-means-government-ideologues-exit|title=An ideologue's exit|date=11 May 2013|newspaper=The Economist|issn=0013-0613|access-date=20 November 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn [[Western media]] outside Russia, a vocal and eloquent [[critic]] of Surkov and of the [[Presidency of Vladimir Putin|administration of Vladimir Putin]] in general has been [[Peter Pomerantsev]]. Pomerantsev has written [[op-ed]]s in ''[[The Atlantic]]'',<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theatlantic.com/international/archive/2014/09/russia-putin-revolutionizing-information-warfare/379880/|title=Russia and the Menace of Unreality|last=Pomerantsev|first=Peter|date=9 September 2014|work=|newspaper=The Atlantic|language=en-US|access-date=20 November 2016|via=}}</ref> ''[[The New York Times]]'',<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2014/12/12/opinion/russias-ideology-there-is-no-truth.html|title=Russia's Ideology: There Is No Truth|last=Pomerantsev|first=Peter|date=11 December 2014|newspaper=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|access-date=20 November 2016}}</ref> and the ''[[London Review of Books]]''<ref name=\"LOB01\" /><ref name=\":1\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.lrb.co.uk/blog/2013/05/08/peter-pomerantsev/the-empty-chair/|title=Peter Pomerantsev: Goodbye Surkov|website=LRB blog|access-date=20 November 2016}}</ref> accusing Surkov, \"Putin's chief [[Ideology|ideologue]]\" with \"unsurpassed influence over Russian politics\", of turning Russia into a \"[[Managed Democracy|managed democracy]]\", and of reducing [[Politics of Russia|Russian politics]] to nothing but \"[[Postmodern theatre|postmodernist theatre]]\". In a talk before the [[Legatum Institute]], Pomerantsev, along with [[Pavel Khodorkovsky]], termed Russia a \"[[postmodern]] [[dictatorship]]\".<ref>{{Citation|last=|title=Russia: A Postmodern Dictatorship? With Pavel Khodorkovsky & Peter Pomerantsev|date=14 October 2013|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=qMIHmzgzVBU|publication-date=|publisher=Legatum Institute|accessdate=20 November 2016}}</ref>\n\n=== Rumored pseudonym of Nathan Dubovitsky ===\nOn 13 August 2009, Russian business newspaper ''[[Vedomosti]]'' reported that an anonymous source told them that a recently released novel, ''Close to Zero'' (''{{Lang-ru|[[:ru:\u041e\u043a\u043e\u043b\u043e\u043d\u043e\u043b\u044f|\u041e\u043a\u043e\u043b\u043e\u043d\u043e\u043b\u044f]]|link=no}}''), was written by Surkov under the pseudonym Nathan Dubovitsky ({{Lang-ru|\u041d\u0430\u0442\u0430\u043d \u0414\u0443\u0431\u043e\u0432\u0438\u0446\u043a\u0438\u0439|link=no}}) in the magazine Russian Pioneer ({{Lang-ru|[[:ru:\u0420\u0443\u0441\u0441\u043a\u0438\u0439 \u043f\u0438\u043e\u043d\u0435\u0440|\u0420\u0443\u0441\u0441\u043a\u0438\u0439 \u043f\u0438\u043e\u043d\u0435\u0440]]|link=no}}). It was soon realized that the pseudonym is almost identical to the name of Surkov's second and current wife, Natalya Dubovitskaya ({{Lang-ru|\u041d\u0430\u0442\u0430\u043b\u044c\u044f \u0414\u0443\u0431\u043e\u0432\u0438\u0446\u043a\u0430\u044f|link=no}}).<ref name=\":3\" />\n\nIn a subsequent edition of ''Close to Zero'', Surkov would write a preface to it under his real name, but would continue to deny writing the main text. In the preface, Surkov writes two seemingly contradictory statements: \"The author of this novel is an unoriginal Hamlet-obsessed hack\"; and, \"this is the best book I have ever read\".<ref name=\"LOB01\" /> Furthermore, the debut performance of the [[Play (theatre)|theatrical version]] of the novel, [[Theatre director|directed]] by [[Kirill Serebrennikov]], was attended by Surkov.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.kp.ru/daily/25625.5/792155/|title=\"\u041e\u043a\u043e\u043b\u043e\u043d\u043e\u043b\u044f\": \u0447\u0451\u0440\u043d\u043e\u0435 \u043d\u0430 \u0447\u0451\u0440\u043d\u043e\u043c|last=Dementsova|first=Emilia|date=24 January 2011|work=|newspaper=[[Komsomolskaya Pravda]]|language=Russian|trans-title=\"Close to Zero\": Black on black|quote=And recently I attended a Kirill Serebrennikov play based on the novel \"Close to Zero\", the debut of which was attended by Surkov himself. (\u0418 \u0432\u043e\u0442 \u043d\u0435\u0434\u0430\u0432\u043d\u043e \u0432\u044b\u0448\u0435\u043b \u0441\u043f\u0435\u043a\u0442\u0430\u043a\u043b\u044c \u041a\u0438\u0440\u0438\u043b\u043b\u0430 \u0421\u0435\u0440\u0435\u0431\u0440\u0435\u043d\u0438\u043a\u043e\u0432\u0430 \u043f\u043e \u0440\u043e\u043c\u0430\u043d\u0443 \u00ab\u041e\u043a\u043e\u043b\u043e\u043d\u043e\u043b\u044f\u00bb, \u043d\u0430 \u043f\u0440\u0435\u043c\u044c\u0435\u0440\u0435 \u043a\u043e\u0442\u043e\u0440\u043e\u0433\u043e \u043f\u0440\u0438\u0441\u0443\u0442\u0441\u0442\u0432\u043e\u0432\u0430\u043b \u0438 \u0441\u0430\u043c \u0421\u0443\u0440\u043a\u043e\u0432.)|access-date=20 November 2016|via=}}</ref>\n\nThe novel, which has the [[English language]] subtitle \"gangsta fiction\", has as its [[protagonist]] a man by the name of Yegor Samokhodov. Samokhodov's occupation is [[public relations]], and he is tasked with managing the reputation of a [[List of current heads of federal subjects of Russia|regional governor]]. First, he hires a writer to [[Ghostwriter|ghostwrite]] a piece of [[poetry]] to be published under the name of the governor without disclosing the ghostwriting, so that the governor may win an award and seem clever to his constituents. He then [[Bribery|bribes]] a [[Journalist|newspaper reporter]] to \"correct\" stories that portray the governor negatively, such as allegations that a [[factory]] of a [[Nepotism|relative of his]] is [[Air pollution|releasing chemicals into the air]] that harm local children.<ref name=\":2\" /> The [[publishing houses]] and public relations firms in the novel are intensely violent, with each company having its own [[Street gang|gang]] and [[wikt:turf war|turf war]]s being fought over the [[Publishing rights|rights to publish]] or [[Talent agent|represent]] such acclaimed [[Russian authors]] as [[Alexander Pushkin]] and [[Vladimir Nabokov]].<ref name=\"LOB01\" /> Peter Pomerantsev described the book as \"exactly the sort of book [[Nashi (youth movement)|Surkov's youth groups]] burn on [[Red Square]].\"<ref name=\"LOB01\" /> ''The Economist'' wrote that the novel \"expos[ed] the vices of the system [Surkov] himself had created\".<ref>[http://www.economist.com/node/21541444 \"The long life of Homo sovieticus\"]. ''The Economist''. 10 December 2011 (issue date). Retrieved 8 December 2011.</ref>\n\nOther works authored under the name Nathan Dubovitsky, all published in Russian Pioneer, that are rumored to be the work of Surkov are:\n* ''The Little Car and the Bicycle [gaga saga]'' ({{Lang-ru|\u041c\u0430\u0448\u0438\u043d\u043a\u0430 \u0438 \u0412\u0435\u043b\u0438\u043a [gaga saga]|Mashinka i Velik [gaga saga]|link=no}}) (2012) <ref>{{Cite news|url=http://grandmotherafrica.com/cloudless-sky-short-story-nathan-dubovitsky/|title=A Cloudless Sky \u2013 A Short Story By Nathan Dubovitsky \u2013 Grandmother Africa|last=Nefekare|first=Jehuti|date=2 February 2015|newspaper=Grandmother Africa|language=en-US|access-date=20 November 2016}}</ref>\n* ''Uncle Vanya [cover version]'' (2014) ({{Lang-ru|\u0414\u044f\u0434\u044f \u0412\u0430\u043d\u044f [cover version]|link=no}})<ref>http://ruspioner.ru/cool/m/single/4103</ref>\n* ''Without Sky'' (2014) ({{Lang-ru|\u0411\u0435\u0437 \u043d\u0435\u0431\u0430|link=no}})<ref name=\":1\" />\n*''Ultranormality'' (2017) (Russian: \u0423\u043b\u044c\u0442\u0440\u0430\u043d\u043e\u0440\u043c\u0430\u043b\u044c\u043d\u043e\u0441\u0442\u044c)\n\n=== Influence outside Russia ===\nSome outside Russia, such as Ned Reskinoff of [[ThinkProgress]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://medium.com/@resnikoff/phantasmagoria-3beac7fe516d|title=Phantasmagoria|last=Resnikoff|first=Ned|date=26 September 2016|website=Medium|access-date=19 November 2016}}</ref> and [[Adam Curtis]] in the [[BBC News|BBC]] documentary ''[[HyperNormalisation]]'',<ref name=\":6\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/iplayer/episode/p04b183c/adam-curtis-hypernormalisation|title=Adam Curtis, HyperNormalisation|website=BBC iPlayer|access-date=19 November 2016}}</ref> have claimed that Surkov's unique blend of politics and theatre have begun to affect countries outside of Russia,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/p074j379|title=BBC Radio 4 - Seriously..., The Puppet Master \u2013 Episode 1. Snipers|publisher=BBC|language=en-GB|access-date=5 April 2019}}</ref> most notably the United States with the selection of [[Donald Trump]] for the [[Republican Party presidential primaries, 2016|2016 US Republican nomination]] and Trump's [[Donald Trump presidential campaign, 2016|subsequent campaign]] and [[2016 United States presidential election|election victory]].\n\nIn an editorial for the ''[[London Review of Books]]'' quoted by Curtis, [[Peter Pomerantsev]] describes Putin's Russia thus:\n\n{{Quote|text=In contemporary Russia, unlike the old USSR or present-day North Korea, the stage is constantly changing: the country is a dictatorship in the morning, a democracy at lunch, an oligarchy by suppertime, while, backstage, oil companies are expropriated, journalists killed, billions siphoned away. Surkov is at the centre of the show, sponsoring nationalist skinheads one moment, backing human rights groups the next. It's a strategy of power based on keeping any opposition there may be constantly confused, a ceaseless shape-shifting that is unstoppable because it's indefinable.|sign=[[Peter Pomerantsev]]|source=in \"Putin's Rasputin\", ''[[London Review of Books]]'' issue of 20 October 2011<ref name=LOB01/>}}\n\nCurtis claims that Trump used a similar strategy to become [[president of the United States]], and hints that Trump's Surkovian origins caused Putin to express his admiration for Trump in [[Russian media]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/2016/oct/09/adam-curtis-donald-trump-documentary-hypernormalisation|title=Adam Curtis continues search for the hidden forces behind a century of chaos|last=Adams|first=Tim|date=9 October 2016|newspaper=The Guardian|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077|access-date=20 November 2016}}</ref><ref>{{Cite AV media|title=[[HyperNormalisation]]|year=2016|medium=BBC iPlayer|people=[[Adam Curtis]]}}</ref>\n\nSurkov has boasted that \"Russia is playing with the West\u2019s minds\", \"They don't know how to deal with their own changed consciousness.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/europe/putin-russia-kremlin-vladislav-surkov-grey-cardinal-moscow-a8773661.html|title=Russia is 'playing with the West's minds' says Putin advisor|newspaper=[[The Independent]]|last=Carroll|first=Oliver|date=12 February 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nSurkov has married twice. His first marriage, to Yulia Petrovna Vishnevskaya ({{Lang-ru|\u042e\u043b\u0438\u044f \u041f\u0435\u0442\u0440\u043e\u0432\u043d\u0430 \u0412\u0438\u0448\u043d\u0435\u0432\u0441\u043a\u0430\u044f|link=no}}) in 1987, ended in divorce in 1996. In his second marriage, Surkov married Natalya Dubovitskaya, his secretary when he was an executive at the [[Bank Menatep|Menatep]] bank, in a civil ceremony in 1998.<ref name=\"lenta.ru\"/><ref>[http://www.anticompromat.org/surkov/surkbio.html Surkov bio] anticompromat.ru</ref><ref name=\":4\">{{Cite web|url= http://www.uznayvse.ru/znamenitosti/biografiya-vladislav-surkov.html|title= \u0412\u043b\u0430\u0434\u0438\u0441\u043b\u0430\u0432 \u0421\u0443\u0440\u043a\u043e\u0432 \u0431\u0438\u043e\u0433\u0440\u0430\u0444\u0438\u044f, \u0444\u043e\u0442\u043e, \u0435\u0433\u043e \u0436\u0435\u043d\u0430 \u0438 \u0441\u0435\u043c\u044c\u044f|last= |first= |date= |website= www.uznayvse.ru|publisher= |language= Russian|trans-title= Vladislav Surkov, biography, photos, his wife and family|access-date= 20 November 2016}}</ref> Surkov has four children: [[Artem Surkov|Artem]] ({{Lang-ru|\u0410\u0440\u0442\u0451\u043c|link=no}}; born 15 October 1993),<ref name=\":4\"/><ref>{{cite web|title= \u0421\u0443\u0440\u043a\u043e\u0432 \u0410\u0440\u0442\u0451\u043c \u041e\u043b\u0435\u0433\u043e\u0432\u0438\u0447 (Artem Olegovich Surkov)|url= http://wrestrus.ru/users/5131|website= Russian Wrestling Federation|publisher= \u0424\u0435\u0434\u0435\u0440\u0430\u0446\u0438\u044f \u0441\u043f\u043e\u0440\u0442\u0438\u0432\u043d\u043e\u0439 \u0431\u043e\u0440\u044c\u0431\u044b \u0420\u043e\u0441\u0441\u0438\u0438|accessdate= 23 November 2016}}</ref> the biological child of Yulia he adopted during his first marriage; and Roman ({{Lang-ru|\u0420\u043e\u043c\u0430\u043d|link=no}}; born 2002),<ref name=\":7\">{{Cite web|url= http://kremlin.ru/structure/administration/income-reports|title= Data on income, property and property obligations of federal officials of the Presidential Administration and the Security Council of Russia, as well as their spouses and minor children for the period from 1 January 2010 to 31 December 2010 (\u0421\u0432\u0435\u0434\u0435\u043d\u0438\u044f \u043e \u0434\u043e\u0445\u043e\u0434\u0430\u0445, \u043e\u0431 \u0438\u043c\u0443\u0449\u0435\u0441\u0442\u0432\u0435 \u0438 \u043e\u0431\u044f\u0437\u0430\u0442\u0435\u043b\u044c\u0441\u0442\u0432\u0430\u0445 \u0438\u043c\u0443\u0449\u0435\u0441\u0442\u0432\u0435\u043d\u043d\u043e\u0433\u043e \u0445\u0430\u0440\u0430\u043a\u0442\u0435\u0440\u0430 \u0444\u0435\u0434\u0435\u0440\u0430\u043b\u044c\u043d\u044b\u0445 \u0433\u043e\u0441\u0443\u0434\u0430\u0440\u0441\u0442\u0432\u0435\u043d\u043d\u044b\u0445 \u0441\u043b\u0443\u0436\u0430\u0449\u0438\u0445 \u0410\u0434\u043c\u0438\u043d\u0438\u0441\u0442\u0440\u0430\u0446\u0438\u0438 \u041f\u0440\u0435\u0437\u0438\u0434\u0435\u043d\u0442\u0430 \u0438 \u0430\u043f\u043f\u0430\u0440\u0430\u0442\u0430 \u0421\u043e\u0432\u0435\u0442\u0430 \u0411\u0435\u0437\u043e\u043f\u0430\u0441\u043d\u043e\u0441\u0442\u0438 \u0420\u043e\u0441\u0441\u0438\u0438, \u0430 \u0442\u0430\u043a\u0436\u0435 \u0438\u0445 \u0441\u0443\u043f\u0440\u0443\u0433\u043e\u0432 \u0438 \u043d\u0435\u0441\u043e\u0432\u0435\u0440\u0448\u0435\u043d\u043d\u043e\u043b\u0435\u0442\u043d\u0438\u0445 \u0434\u0435\u0442\u0435\u0439 \u0437\u0430 \u043f\u0435\u0440\u0438\u043e\u0434 \u0441 1 \u044f\u043d\u0432\u0430\u0440\u044f 2010\u0433. \u043f\u043e 31 \u0434\u0435\u043a\u0430\u0431\u0440\u044f 2010\u0433.)|last= |first= |date= 2010|website= Official [[Kremlin]] Website|publisher= |access-date= }}</ref> Maria ({{Lang-ru|\u041c\u0430\u0440\u0438\u044f|link= no}}; born 2004),<ref name=\":7\" /> and Timur ({{Lang-ru|\u0422\u0438\u043c\u0443\u0440|link= no}}; born 2010),<ref name=\":7\" /> biological children of himself and Natalya.<ref name=\":4\" />\n\nSurkov has composed songs<ref name=LOB01/> and written texts for the Russian rock-musician Vadim Samoylov, ex-member of the band [[Agatha Christie (band)|Agata Kristi]] ({{lang-ru|\u0410\u0433\u0430\u0442\u0430 \u041a\u0440\u0438\u0441\u0442\u0438}}). He speaks English and is fond of poets of the [[Beat Generation]] such as [[Allen Ginsberg]].<ref name=RE01>\nFaulconbridge, Guy [https://www.reuters.com/article/2011/09/16/us-russia-prokhorov-surkov-idUSTRE78F2TB20110916 \"Kremlin \"puppet master\" faces errant oligarch\"]. Reuters. 16 September 2011. Retrieved 21 September 2011.\n</ref>\n\n==Honours and awards==\n* [[Order of Merit for the Fatherland]], 3rd class (13 November 2003) \u2013 for outstanding contribution to strengthening Russian statehood and many years of diligent work\n* Gratitude of the President of the Russian Federation (18 January 2010, 12 June 2004 and 8 July 2003) \u2013 for active participation in the preparation of the President's address to the Federal Assembly of the Russian Federation\n* Medal of PA Stolypin, 2nd class (21 September 2011)\n* Diploma of the [[Central Election Commission of the Russian Federation]] (2 April 2008) \u2013 for active support and substantial assistance in organizing and conducting the elections of the President of the Russian Federation\n* State Councillor of the Russian Federation, 1st class\n\n==See also==\n*[[Mikhail Lesin]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* Bovt, Georgii. \"Vladislav Surkov: A Pragmatic Idealism.\" ''Russian Politics & Law'' 46#5 (2008): 33\u201340.\n*  M\u00e4kinen, Sirke. \"Surkovian narrative on the future of Russia: making Russia a world leader.\" ''Journal of Communist Studies and Transition Politics'' 27#2 (2011): 143\u2013165.\n* Sakwa, Richard. \"Russian Political Culture Through the Eyes of Vladislav Surkov\" ''Russian Politics & Law'' 46.5 (2008): 3\u20137.\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Vladislav Surkov}}\n* [http://en.kremlin.ru/catalog/persons/2/biography Official record]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20140427010955/http://russiaprofile.org/bg_people/resources_whoiswho_alphabet_s_surkov.html Russia Profile Who's Who]\n* [https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/p074j379 The Puppet Master - \"This is the story of the most powerful man you\u2019ve never heard of\" - BBC Radio 4 Podcast \"Seriously\u2026\"]\n* [http://users2.wsj.com/lmda/do/checkLogin?mg=wsj-users2&url=http%3A%2F%2Fonline.wsj.com%2Farticle%2FSB116646992809753610.html%3Fmod%3DITPWSJ_1 Surkov: In His Own Words. The Wall Street Journal. 18 December 2006]\n* [http://lenta.ru/lib/14159273/full.htm Biography @ Lenta.ru]\n* [https://www.bbc.co.uk/blogs/adamcurtis/2012/01/the_years_of_stagnation_and_th.html The Years of Stagnation and the Poodles of Power], [[Adam Curtis]] blog at BBC\n* [http://www.lrb.co.uk/v33/n20/peter-pomerantsev/putins-rasputin Putin's Rasputin], by [[Peter Pomerantsev]] in [[London Review of Books]]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20150201203715/http://allpersons.name/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=528&Itemid=12 Biography Surkov] (Russian)\n\n{{Current Russian Cabinet}}\n{{Ukrainian crisis navbox}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Surkov, Vladislav Yuryevich}}\n[[Category:Aides to the President of Russia]]\n[[Category:GRU officers]]\n[[Category:Russian businesspeople]]\n[[Category:Medvedev Administration personnel]]\n[[Category:United Russia politicians]]\n[[Category:People of the annexation of Crimea by the Russian Federation]]\n[[Category:Pro-Russian people of the 2014 pro-Russian unrest in Ukraine]]\n[[Category:Moscow Institute of Steel and Alloys alumni]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Order \"For Merit to the Fatherland\", 3rd class]]\n[[Category:People from Chaplyginsky District]]\n[[Category:People from Shalinsky District, Chechen Republic]]\n[[Category:People of the Ukrainian crisis]]\n[[Category:Russian people of Chechen descent]]\n[[Category:1964 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:20th-century Russian politicians]]\n[[Category:21st-century Russian politicians]]\n", "name_user": "Abbyjjjj96", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eEarly years:reordered to match order of previous sentence", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Vladislav_Surkov"}
{"title_page": "Le Voyageur sans bagage", "text_new": "{{italic title}}\n{{refimprove|date=July 2011}}\n'''''Le Voyageur sans bagage''''' (''The Traveller Without Luggage'') is a 1937 [[play (theatre)|play]] in five acts by [[Jean Anouilh]].  [[Incidental music]] for the original production was written by [[Darius Milhaud]].\n\n==Plot==\nGaston, a veteran of [[World War I]], suffers from [[amnesia]] and has spent the last 18 years in a hospital trying to regain his memories. Although he's claimed as a son by various families, a rich Duchess believes the true family Gaston belongs to is the Renauds. Gaston travels to the Renauds' estate alongside his lawyer, Huspar. A docile character, Gaston discovers his former identity of Jacques Renaud: a cruel and violent young man who used to kill animals for sport. He learns that immediately prior to the war he pushed his best friend, Marcel, down a flight of stairs, breaking his back, shortly after seeing him kiss the maid Juliette, with whom Jacques had been intimate. Gaston has difficulty reconciling his current personality with that of his past. His brother's wife, Valentine (with whom he had an affair during adolescence), tells him about a tiny scar on his shoulder, sustained when Valentine attacked him with a hat pin in a fit of jealousy. Gaston sees this scar in a mirror but doesn't tell Valentine about it. Soon thereafter, numerous families arrive at the Renaud estate, searching for their lost loved one from the war. Gaston spots a young boy. This boy, who is the only surviving member of the Madensales, a family who died in a boating accident when he was an infant, is searching for his long-lost nephew who happens to be much older than himself. Gaston tells the young boy about the scar on his shoulder and fabricates a story about the scar belonging to the boy's long-lost nephew. Gaston leaves the Renauds to become a member of the boy's family, later writing a letter to Jacques' brother Georges, stating that their Jacques is dead and they need not search for him any longer.\n\n==Inspiration and reception==\nInspired by the story of an amnesiac soldier, [[Anthelme Mangin]], who was claimed by over a dozen families,<ref>Jean Yves Le Naour, ''Le Soldat inconnu vivant'', 2002.</ref> the play was Anouilh's first major critical success and helped his career as a playwright flourish.\n\n==Original productions==\n\n'''Paris''' \u2013 Th\u00e9\u00e2tre des Mathurins, 16 February 1937\n\n*Gaston \u2013 [[Georges Pito\u00ebff]]\n*Georges Renaud \u2013 [[Louis Salou]]\n*Mme Renaud \u2013 [[Marthe Mellot]]\n*Valentine Renaud \u2013 Nadine Picard\n*La duchesse Dupont-Dufort \u2013 Nora Sylv\u00e8re\n*Ma\u00eetre Huspar \u2013 Raymond Dagand\n*Le petit gar\u00e7on \u2013 Ludmilla Pito\u00ebff\n*Ma\u00eetre Picwick \u2013 Henri Grall\n*Le ma\u00eetre d\u2019h\u00f4tel \u2013 Henri Gaultier\n*Le chauffeur \u2013 [[L\u00e9on Larive]]\n*Le valet de chambre \u2013 [[Gabriel Gobin]]\n* La cuisini\u00e8re \u2013 [[Andr\u00e9e Tainsy]]\n*Juliette \u2013 [[Madeleine Milhaud]]\n\nDirected by [[Georges Pito\u00ebff]]\n\n'''London''' \u2013 ''Traveller Without Luggage'' \u2013 Arts Theatre, 29 January 1959\n\n*Gaston \u2013 [[Denholm Elliott]]\n*Georges Renaud \u2013 [[Geoffrey Keen]]\n*Mme Renaud \u2013 [[Irene Browne]]\n*Valentine Renaud \u2013 [[Elizabeth Sellars]]\n*The Duchesse Dupont-Dufort \u2013 [[Joyce Carey]]\n*Ma\u00eetre Huspar \u2013 [[Douglas Wilmer]]\n*a small boy \u2013 Hugh James\n*Ma\u00eetre Picwick \u2013 Norman Pitt\n*A butler \u2013 Anthony Blake\n*A chauffeur \u2013 James Wellman\n*A valet \u2013 John Warner\n*A cook \u2013 [[Peggy Ann Clifford]]\n*Juliette \u2013 Violetta\n\nDirected by [[Peter Hall]]\n\nTranslated by [[John Whiting]]\n\n'''New York''' \u2013 ''Traveller Without Luggage'' \u2013 ANTA Playhouse, 17 September 1964\n\n*Gaston \u2013 [[Ben Gazzara]]\n*Georges Renaud \u2013 [[Stephen Elliott (actor)|Stephen Elliott]]\n*Mme Renaud \u2013 [[Mildred Dunnock]]\n*Valentine Renaud \u2013 [[Nancy Wickwire]]\n*The Duchesse Dupont-Dufort \u2013 Margaret Braidwood\n*Ma\u00eetre Huspar \u2013 Boris Tumarin\n*A small boy \u2013 Jeffrey Neal\n*Mr Truggle [ie, Ma\u00eetre Picwick] \u2013 Ronald Dawson\n*A butler \u2013 William Cottrell\n*A valet \u2013 Anthony Palmer\n*Juliette \u2013 [[Rae Allen]]\n\nDirected by [[Robert Lewis (actor)|Robert Lewis]]\n\nTranslated by [[Lucienne Hill]]\n\n==Adaptations==\nThe play has been adapted several times, firstly as [[Traveling Light (1944 film)|a film in 1944]], directed by Anouilh himself, and then several times on television: in Great Britain (October 1959 and February 1965), Australia (August 1961), Canada (January 1962), Spain (February 1964 and February 1968), and France (September 2004, directed by [[Pierre Boutron]]). A new stage adaptation by Anthony Weigh, transposed to 1950s America and titled ''Welcome Home, Captain Fox!'', was produced at London's [[Donmar Warehouse]] in March 2016.\n\nIn India, on Mumbai (Bombay) Doordarshan TV the play was directed in Marathi by celebrated Marathi director Chandrakant Kulkarni and performed by Bhakti Barve Inamdar, Tushar Dalvi (title role), Aardra Athalye (small boy), Prasad Athalye and others. The play's Marathi name was ''Ozyawina Pravashi''.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n*Anouilh, Jean: ''Le Voyageur sans bagage''. Paris: Folio, 2002.\n*Anouilh, Jean: ''Traveller Without Luggage''. London: Methuen, 1959. [Translated by John Whiting.]\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb title|id=0141969|title=Le Voyageur sans bagages (1944)}}\n* {{IMDb title|id=0409448|title=Le Voyageur sans bagages (2004)}}\n\n{{Jean Anouilh}}\n{{Darius Milhaud}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Voyageur Sans Baggage, Le}}\n[[Category:French plays adapted into films]]\n[[Category:Plays by Jean Anouilh]]\n[[Category:1937 plays]]\n[[Category:Incidental music]]\n\n\n{{1930s-play-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{italic title}}\n{{refimprove|date=July 2011}}\n'''''Le Voyageur sans bagage''''' (''The Traveller Without Luggage'') is a 1937 [[play (theatre)|play]] in five acts by [[Jean Anouilh]].  [[Incidental music]] for the original production was written by [[Darius Milhaud]].\n\n==Plot==\nGaston, a veteran of [[World War I]], suffers from [[amnesia]] and has spent the last 18 years in a hospital trying to regain his memories. Although he's claimed as a son by various families, a rich Duchess believes the true family Gaston belongs to is the Renauds. Gaston travels to the Renauds' estate alongside his lawyer, Huspar. A docile character, Gaston discovers his former identity of Jacques Renaud: a cruel and violent young man who used to kill animals for sport. He learns that immediately prior to the war he pushed his best friend, Marcel, down a flight of stairs, breaking his back, shortly after seeing him kiss the maid Juliette, with whom Jacques had been intimate. Gaston has difficulty reconciling his current personality with that of his past. His brother's wife, Valentine (with whom he had an affair during adolescence), tells him about a tiny scar on his shoulder, sustained when Valentine attacked him with a hat pin in a fit of jealousy. Gaston sees this scar in a mirror but doesn't tell Valentine about it. Soon thereafter, numerous families arrive at the Renaud estate, searching for their lost loved one from the war. Gaston spots a young boy. This boy, who is the only surviving member of the Madensales, a family who died in a boating accident when he was an infant, is searching for his long-lost nephew who happens to be much older than himself. Gaston tells the young boy about the scar on his shoulder and fabricates a story about the scar belonging to the boy's long-lost nephew. Gaston leaves the Renauds to become a member of the boy's family, later writing a letter to Jacques' brother Georges, stating that their Jacques is dead and they need not search for him any longer.\n\n==Inspiration and reception==\nInspired by the story of an amnesiac soldier, [[Anthelme Mangin]], who was claimed by over a dozen families,<ref>Jean Yves Le Naour, ''Le Soldat inconnu vivant'', 2002.</ref> the play was Anouilh's first major critical success and helped his career as a playwright flourish.\n\n==Original productions==\n\n'''Paris''' \u2013 Th\u00e9\u00e2tre des Mathurins, 16 February 1937\n\n*Gaston \u2013 [[Georges Pito\u00ebff]]\n*Georges Renaud \u2013 [[Louis Salou]]\n*Mme Renaud \u2013 [[Marthe Mellot]]\n*Valentine Renaud \u2013 Nadine Picard\n*La duchesse Dupont-Dufort \u2013 Nora Sylv\u00e8re\n*Ma\u00eetre Huspar \u2013 Raymond Dagand\n*Le petit gar\u00e7on \u2013 Ludmilla Pito\u00ebff\n*Ma\u00eetre Picwick \u2013 Henri Grall\n*Le ma\u00eetre d\u2019h\u00f4tel \u2013 Henri Gaultier\n*Le chauffeur \u2013 [[L\u00e9on Larive]]\n*Le valet de chambre \u2013 [[Gabriel Gobin]]\n* La cuisini\u00e8re \u2013 [[Andr\u00e9e Tainsy]]\n*Juliette \u2013 [[Madeleine Milhaud]]\n\nDirected by [[Georges Pito\u00ebff]]\n\n'''London''' \u2013 ''Traveller Without Luggage'' \u2013 Arts Theatre, 29 January 1959\n\n*Gaston \u2013 [[Denholm Elliott]]\n*Georges Renaud \u2013 [[Geoffrey Keen]]\n*Mme Renaud \u2013 [[Irene Browne]]\n*Valentine Renaud \u2013 [[Elizabeth Sellars]]\n*The Duchesse Dupont-Dufort \u2013 [[Joyce Carey]]\n*Ma\u00eetre Huspar \u2013 [[Douglas Wilmer]]\n*a small boy \u2013 Hugh James\n*Ma\u00eetre Picwick \u2013 Norman Pitt\n*A butler \u2013 Anthony Blake\n*A chauffeur \u2013 James Wellman\n*A valet \u2013 John Warner\n*A cook \u2013 [[Peggy Ann Clifford]]\n*Juliette \u2013 Violetta\n\nDirected by [[Peter Hall]]\n\nTranslated by [[John Whiting]]\n\n'''New York''' \u2013 ''Traveller Without Luggage'' \u2013 ANTA Playhouse, 17 September 1964\n\n*Gaston \u2013 [[Ben Gazzara]]\n*Georges Renaud \u2013 [[Stephen Elliott (actor)|Stephen Elliott]]\n*Mme Renaud \u2013 [[Mildred Dunnock]]\n*Valentine Renaud \u2013 [[Nancy Wickwire]]\n*The Duchesse Dupont-Dufort \u2013 Margaret Braidwood\n*Ma\u00eetre Huspar \u2013 Boris Tumarin\n*A small boy \u2013 Jeffrey Neal\n*Mr Truggle [ie, Ma\u00eetre Picwick] \u2013 Ronald Dawson\n*A butler \u2013 William Cottrell\n*A valet \u2013 Anthony Palmer\n*Juliette \u2013 [[Rae Allen]]\n\nDirected by [[Robert Lewis (actor)|Robert Lewis]]\n\nTranslated by [[Lucienne Hill]]\n\n==Adaptations==\nThe play has been adapted several times, firstly as [[Traveling Light (1944 film)|a film in 1944]], directed by Anouilh himself, and then several times on television: in Great Britain (October 1959 and February 1965), Australia (August 1961), Canada (January 1962), Spain (February 1964 and February 1968), and France (September 2004, directed by [[Pierre Boutron]]). A new stage adaptation by Anthony Weigh, transposed to 1950s America and titled ''Welcome Home, Captain Fox!'', was produced at London's [[Donmar Warehouse]] in March 2016.\n\nIn India, on Mumbai (Bombay) Doordarshan TV the play was directed in Marathi by celebrated Marathi director Chandrakant Kulkarni and performed by Bhakti Barve Inamdar, Tushar Dalvi (title role), Aardra Athalye (small boy), Prasad Athalye and others. The play's Marathi name was ''Ozyawina Pravashi''.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n*Anouilh, Jean: ''Le voyageur sans bagage''. Paris: Folio, 2002.\n*Anouilh, Jean: ''Traveller Without Luggage''. London: Methuen, 1959. [Translated by John Whiting.]\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb title|id=0141969|title=Le Voyageur sans bagages (1944)}}\n* {{IMDb title|id=0409448|title=Le Voyageur sans bagages (2004)}}\n\n{{Jean Anouilh}}\n{{Darius Milhaud}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Voyageur Sans Baggage, Le}}\n[[Category:French plays adapted into films]]\n[[Category:Plays by Jean Anouilh]]\n[[Category:1937 plays]]\n[[Category:Incidental music]]\n\n\n{{1930s-play-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Clamias", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eReferences", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Le_Voyageur_sans_bagage"}
{"title_page": "National responses to the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic", "text_new": "{{pp-semi-indef|small=yes}}\n{{Short description|Internal responses of the nations of the world.}}\n{{About|government responses to the outbreak|information on the status of the outbreak by country|2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic by country and territory}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Current disaster|event=pandemic|date=March 2020}}\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic sidebar|expanded=issues}}\n[[File:Tree- How Covid-19 spreads.png|thumb|right|upright=1.4]]\n'''National responses to the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic''' have been varied, and have included containment measures such as [[lockdowns|lockdown]], [[quarantines|quarantine]], and [[curfews|curfew]].<ref name=\"WOM\">{{cite web|url=https://www.worldometers.info/coronavirus/|title=Coronavirus Update (Live) \u2013 Worldometer|website=worldometers.info}}</ref>  [[COVID-19]]  has spread to many countries around the world, with the most affected countries being the United States, Italy, Spain, China, France, Iran, Switzerland and South Korea.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Guti\u00e9rrez |first1=Pablo |title=Coronavirus map: how Covid-19 is spreading across the world |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/ng-interactive/2020/mar/24/coronavirus-map-how-covid-19-is-spreading-across-the-world |work=The Guardian}}</ref>\n\n== China ==\n{{Main|2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic in mainland China}}\n{{summarize section|date=April 2020}}\n\n[[File:Staff monitoring passengers' body temperature in Wuhan railway station during the Wuhan coronavirus outbreak.jpg|thumb|Infrared cameras were installed in [[Wuhan railway station]] to check passengers' body temperature before they board the trains.|link=Special:FilePath/Staff_monitoring_passengers'_body_temperature_in_Wuhan_railway_station_during_the_Wuhan_coronavirus_pandemic.jpg]]\n[[File:\u822a\u62cd\u6b66\u6c49\u4e2d\u5fc3\u57ce\u533a\u673a\u52a8\u8f66\u7981\u884c\u540e\u9053\u8def\uff1a\u5c11\u6709\u8f66\u8f86\u8e2a\u5f71-Wg-8rMZAsY0.webm|thumb|right|'Aerial photography of roads after motor vehicles are banned in central urban areas of Wuhan: few vehicle traces' \u2013 Video news from [[China News Service]]]]\n[[File:Changchun Longjia Airport Terminal 2 Security Check (20200126) (cropped).jpg|thumb|right|Masked passengers undergoing temperature checks at [[Changchun Longjia International Airport|Changchun Longjia Airport]] in northeast China]]\n[[File:West Kowloon Station queue 20200125.jpg|thumb|right|Hong Kong residents queueing to refund their [[Hong Kong Express Rail Link|bullet train]] tickets to the mainland in [[West Kowloon railway station]]]]\nThe first person known to have fallen ill due to the new virus was in Wuhan on 1 December 2019.<ref name=\"AutoDW-67\"/> A public notice on the outbreak was released by Wuhan health authority on 31 December; the initial notice informed Wuhan residents that there was no clear evidence of human-to-human transmission of the virus, that the disease is preventable and controllable, and that people can wear masks when going out.<ref name=\"AutoDW-68\"/> WHO was informed of the outbreak on the same day.<ref name=\"AutoDW-69\"/>\n\nOn 7 January 2020, the Chinese [[Politburo Standing Committee of the Communist Party of China|Communist Party Politburo Standing Committee]] discussed novel coronavirus prevention and control.<ref name=\"Xi's meeting\"/><ref name=\"Xi's meeting 2\"/>\n\nOn 20 January, [[Zhong Nanshan]], a scientist at China's [[National Health Commission]] who played a prominent role in the SARS epidemic, declared its potential for human-to-human transmission, after two cases emerged in [[Guangdong]] of infection by family members who had visited Wuhan.<ref name=\"AutoDW-70\"/> This was later confirmed by the Wuhan government, which announced a number of new measures such as cancelling the [[Chinese New Year]] celebrations, in addition to measures such as checking the temperature of passengers at transport terminals first introduced on 14 January.<ref name=\"AutoDW-71\"/> A [[2020 Hubei lockdowns|quarantine]] was announced on 23 January 2020 stopping travel in and out of Wuhan.<ref name=\"channelnewsasia12306684\"/>\n\nOn 25 January, Chinese authorities banned the use of private vehicles in [[Wuhan]]. Only vehicles that are transporting critical supplies or emergency response vehicles are allowed to move within the city.<ref name=\"abc11902006\"/>\n\nOn 26 January, a leading group tasked with the prevention and control of the novel coronavirus pandemic was established, led by [[Premier of the People's Republic of China|Chinese Premier]] [[Li Keqiang]].<ref name=\"Premier leading\"/><ref name=\"Premier visiting\"/> The leading group decided to extend the Spring Festival [[Golden Week (China)|holiday]] to contain the outbreak.<ref name=\"AutoDW-72\"/>\n\nChina Customs started requiring that all passengers entering and exiting China fill in an extra health declaration form from 26 January. The health declaration form was mentioned in China's Frontier Health and Quarantine Law, granting the customs rights to require it if needed.<ref name=\"AutoDW-73\"/><ref name=\"xinhuanet1125502381\"/><ref name=\"20200126cgtn\"/>\n\nOn 27 January, the [[General Office of the State Council]] of China, one of the top governing bodies of the People's Republic, officially declared a nation-wide extension on the New Year holiday and the postponement of the coming spring semester. The office extended the previously scheduled [[Public holidays in China|public holiday]] from 30 January, to 2 February, while it said school openings for the spring semester would be announced in the future.<ref name=\"xinhuanet138735904\"/> Some universities with open campuses also banned the public from visiting.<ref name=\"bjnews678863\"/> On 23 January, the education department in [[Hunan]], which neighbours the centre of the outbreak Hubei province, stated it would strictly ban off-school tutors and restrict student gatherings.<ref name=\"xinhuanet1125498917\"/> Education departments in Shanghai and Shenzhen also imposed bans on off-school tutoring and requested that schools track and report students who had been to Wuhan or Hubei province during the winter break.<ref name=\"xinhuanet138732282\"/><ref name=\"people33743688\"/> The semi-autonomous regions of Hong Kong and [[Macau]] also announced adjustments on schooling schedules. Hong Kong's [[Chief Executive of Hong Kong|Chief Executive]] [[Carrie Lam]] declared an emergency at a press conference on 25 January, saying [[Government of Hong Kong|the government]] would close primary and secondary schools for two more weeks on top of the previously scheduled New Year holiday, pushing the date for school reopening to 17 February.<ref name=\"scmp3047645\"/><ref name=\"apnews-b2810ce\"/> Macau closed several museums and libraries, and prolonged the New Year holiday break to 11 February for higher education institutions and 10 February for others.<ref name=\"xinhuanet1125500373\"/> The [[University of Macau]] said they would track the physical conditions of students who have been to Wuhan during the New Year break.<ref name=\"AutoDW-74\"/>\n\nAfter the Chinese New Year on 25 January, there would be another peak of people travelling back from their home towns to workplaces as a part of Chunyun. Several provinces and cities encouraged people to stay in their hometowns and not travel back. Eastern China's [[Suzhou]] also encouraged [[Telecommuting|remote working]] via the Internet and further prolonged the spring festival break.<ref name=\"CaixinJan26QianTong\"/>\n\nThe [[Civil Aviation Administration of China]] and the [[China Railway|China State Railway Group]], which regulate China's civil aviation and operates rail services, announced on 24 January that passengers could have full refunds for their plane and train tickets without any surcharges, regardless of whether their flight or train will go through Wuhan or not.<ref name=\"20200124reuters-refunds\"/><ref name=\"AutoDW-75\"/> [[Ministry of Culture and Tourism of the People's Republic of China|China's Ministry of Culture and Tourism]] ordered travel agencies and online tourism firms to suspend [[package tour]]s and stop offering \"flight+hotel\" bundles.<ref name=\"CaixinJan26QianTong\" /><ref name=\"20200124bloomberg\"/>\n\nAdditional provinces and cities outside Hubei imposed travel restrictions. Beijing suspended all [[intercity bus service]]s on 25 January,<ref name=\"chinadaily310128217273397\"/> with several others following suit.<ref name=\"CaixinJan26QianTong\" />\n\n[[File:A Screen Display During Wuhan Coronavirus Outbreak.jpg|thumb|right|A screen display in [[Hefei]] showing \"early detection, early reporting, early quarantine, early diagnosis, early treatment\" during the coronavirus pandemic|link=Special:FilePath/A_Screen_Display_During_Wuhan_coronavirus_pandemic.jpg]]\nOn 1 February 2020, Xinhua News reported that China's [[Supreme People's Procuratorate]] (SPP) has \"asked procuratorates nationwide to fully play their role to create a favourable judicial environment in the fight against the novel coronavirus pandemic.\" This includes severe punishments for those found guilty of dereliction of duty and the withholding of information for officials. Tougher charges were proscribed for commercial criminal activities such as \"the pushing up of prices, profiteering and severely disturbing market order\" along with the \"production and sale of fake and shoddy protective equipment and medicines.\" Prosecuting actions against patients who deliberately spread the infection or refuse examination or compulsory isolation along with threats of violence against medical personnel were also urged. The statement also included urging to prosecute those found \"fabricating coronavirus-related information that may lead to panic among the public, making up and spreading rumours about the virus, sabotaging the implementation of the law and endangering public security\" and also stressed \"harshly punishing the illegal hunting of wildlife under state protection, as well as improving inspection and quarantine measures for fresh food and meat products.\"<ref name=\"xinhuanet138747853\"/>\n\nMuseums throughout China are temporarily closed.<ref name=\":12\"/><ref name=\"AutoDW-76\"/> The National Cultural Heritage Administration (NCHA) asked museums around the country to move their exhibits and galleries temporarily online<ref name=\"AutoDW-77\"/> via a program that the NCHA is launching.<ref name=\":12\" /><ref name=\":13\"/>\n\n==== Quarantine ====\n\n{{Main|2020 Hubei lockdowns}}\nOn 23 January 2020, a [[quarantine]] on [[lockdown|travel in and out]] of Wuhan was imposed in an effort to stop the spread of the virus out of Wuhan. Flights, trains, public buses, the metro system, and long-distance coaches were suspended indefinitely. Large-scale gatherings and group tours were also suspended.<ref name=\"channelnewsasia12306684\" /> By 24 January 2020, a total of 15 cities in Hubei, including Wuhan, were placed under similar quarantine measures.<ref name=\":0\"/> On 27 and 28 January 2020, [[Xiangyang]] closed its railway stations and suspended all ferry operations, after shutting down its airport and intercity bus services earlier. Thus, the entire Hubei province entered a city-by-city quarantine, save for the [[Shennongjia]] Forestry District.{{Citation needed|date=February 2020}}\n\nBefore the quarantine began, some in Wuhan questioned the reliability of the figures from the Chinese government as well as the government response, with some calling for quarantine,<ref name=\"bbc51205074\"/> and a post also showed sick people and three dead bodies covered in white sheets on the floor of a hospital on 24 January, although many such posts in Weibo about the epidemic have since been deleted.<ref name=\"20200128nytimes\"/><ref name=\"20200126telegraph\"/>\n\nDue to quarantine measures, Wuhan residents rushed to stockpile essential goods, food, and fuel; prices rose significantly.<ref name=\"20200123reuters\"/><ref name=\"AutoDW-78\"/> 5,000,000 people left Wuhan, with 9,000,000 left in the city.<ref name=\"abc11902378\"/>\n\nOn 26 January, the city of [[Shantou]] in Guangdong declared a partial lockdown,<ref name=\"AutoDW-79\"/> though this was reversed two hours later.<ref name=\"20200126reuters\"/> Residents had rushed to supermarkets to stock food as soon as the lockdown was declared, until the authorities reversed their decision. ''[[Caixin]]'' said, that the wording of Shantou's initial declaration was \"unprecedentedly strict\" and will severely affect residents' lives, if implemented as-is. Shantou's Department for Outbreak Control later clarified that it would not restrict travelling, but would sterilise vehicles used for transportation.<ref name=\"caixin101508610\"/>\n\n<!-- \"Expressway\" and \"highway\" are official terms that should NOT be changed into corresponding British English wordings. \u2022 Beijing's underground transport is called a \"subway,\"\n while ALL other Chinese cities' underground transport is called \"metro\". -->Local authorities in Beijing and several other major cities, including [[Hangzhou]], [[Guangzhou]], Shanghai, and [[Shenzhen]], announced on 26 January, that these cities will not impose a lockdown similar to those in Hubei province. Rumours of these potential lockdowns had spread widely prior to the official announcements.<ref name=\"bjnews680010\"/> A spokesperson of Beijing's Municipal Transportation Commission claimed that the [[Expressways of China|expressways]], [[China National Highways|highways]], [[Beijing subway|subways]], and buses were operating normally. To ease the residents' panic, the Hangzhou city government stressed that the city would not be locked down from the outside world, and both cities said that they would introduce precautions against potential risks.<ref name=\"chinadaily310128217273520\"/>\n\nOn 2 February 2020, the city of [[Wenzhou]] in Zhejiang also implemented a partial lockdown, closing 46 of the 54 highway checkpoints.<ref name=\"20200202wenzhou\"/>\n\nOn 4 February 2020, two more cities in Zhejiang province restricted the movement of residents. The city of [[Taizhou, Zhejiang|Taizhou]], three Hangzhou districts, and some in [[Ningbo]] began to only allow one person per household to go outside every two days to buy necessities, city officials said. More than 12 million people are affected by the new restrictions.<ref name=\"ChannelNewsAsia\"/>\n\nBy 6 February 2020, a total of four Zhejiang cities\u2014Wenzhou, Hangzhou, Ningbo, and Taizhou\u2014were under the \"passport\" system, allowing only one person per household to leave their home every two days. These restrictions apply to over 30&nbsp;million people.<ref name=\"SCMP 20200206\" />\n\nOutside mainland China, some [[2020 coronavirus pandemic on cruise ships|cruise ships]] were quarantined after passengers developed symptoms or tested positive for SARS-CoV-2. The ''[[Costa Smeralda (ship)|Costa Smeralda]]'' was quarantined on 30 January off [[Civitavecchia]] in Italy, after passengers developed flu-like symptoms \u2013 the quarantine was lifted when tests for the virus came back negative.<ref name=\"AutoDW-80\"/> Two further ships were quarantined on 5 February: ''[[Diamond Princess (ship)|Diamond Princess]]'' in the [[Port of Yokohama]], Japan and ''[[World Dream]]'', which returned to Hong Kong after being refused entry to [[Kaohsiung]], Taiwan. In both cases, passengers and crew tested positive.<ref name=\"AutoDW-81\"/><ref name=\"AutoDW-86\" /<ref name=\"cnbcWD\"/><ref name=\"AutoDW-82\"/><ref name=\"AutoDW-83\"/> On 10 February passengers were allowed to disembark the ''World Dream'' \"without the need to self-quarantine after leaving.\"<ref name=\"AutoDW-84\"/>\n\nThe ''Diamond Princess'' was completely disembarked by 1 March, with countries imposing various quarantines for citizens they evacuated.<ref name=\"AutoDW-85\" />> <ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-51555420|title=Growing criticism over Japan cruise quarantine|date=2020-02-20|work=BBC News|access-date=2020-03-26|language=en-GB}}</ref> As of 26 March, 712 people from the ship have been diagnosed and 10 have died.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.worldometers.info/coronavirus/|title=Coronavirus Update (Live): 520,395 Cases and 23,593 Deaths from COVID-19 Virus Outbreak - Worldometer|website=www.worldometers.info|language=en|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref>\n\nAlthough not quarantined {{MS|Westerdam}} has been [[MS Westerdam#2019-20 coronavirus|refused entry]] by several ports after departing Hong Kong on 1 February.<ref>{{cite news |title=Coronavirus: 'Pariah' cruise ship rejected by five ports docks at last |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-51484625 |publisher=BBC News |date=13 February 2020}}</ref>\n<gallery mode=\"packed\" heights=\"150px\">\nFile:Citizens of Wuhan lining up outside of a drug store to buy masks during the Wuhan coronavirus outbreak.jpg|People queueing outside a Wuhan pharmacy to buy face masks and medical supplies\nFile:Wuhan citizens rush to buy vegetables during Wuhan coronavirus outbreak.jpg|Residents of Wuhan wearing masks rushed out to nearby markets to buy vegetables and other food on 23 January during the outbreak\nFile:Last train of Wuhan metro before authorities lock down the city for the Wuhan coronavirus outbreak.jpg|Residents of Wuhan waiting for the last train of the city's metro on 10&nbsp;am, 22 January\n</gallery>\n\n==== Outdoor restrictions ====\nOn 1 February, [[Huanggang]], Hubei implemented a measure whereby only one person from each household is permitted to go outside for provisions once every two days, except for medical reasons or to work at shops or pharmacies.<ref name=\":20\"/>\n{| class=\"wikitable collapsible collapsed sortable\" style=\"text-align:right;\"\n|+ class=\"nowrap\" |<u>'''Administrative divisions with family outdoor restrictions'''</u>\n!Administrative<br />division\n!Division<br />type\n!Provincial<br />division\n!Start date\n!End date\n! data-sort-type=\"number\" |Ordinary<br />population\n!Population<br />year\n!Notes\n|-\n|[[Huanggang]]<ref name=\":20\" />\n|City\n|Hubei\n|2020-02-01\n|\n|6,162,069\n|2010\n|\n|-\n|[[Wenzhou]]<ref name=\"AutoDW-87\"/>\n|City\n|Zhejiang\n|2020-02-02\n|2020-02-08\n|9,190,000\n|2017\n|\n|-\n|[[Wenling]]<ref name=\"AutoDW-88\"/>\n|City\n|Zhejiang\n|2020-02-02\n|\n|1,366,800\n|2010\n|\n|-\n|[[Fangchenggang]]<ref name=\"AutoDW-89\"/>\n|City\n|Guangxi\n|2020-02-02\n|2020-02-08\n|860,100\n|2010\n|\n|-\n|[[Guigang]]<ref name=\"AutoDW-90\"/>\n|City\n|Guangxi\n|2020-02-02\n|\n|1,562,200<br />(Urban only)\n|2010\n|Urban districts only\n|-\n|[[Yuzhou District|Yuzhou]],<ref name=\"auto6\"/> [[Yulin, Guangxi|Yulin]]\n|District\n|Guangxi\n|2020-02-02\n|2020-02-09\n|900,000\n|2010\n|\n|-\n|[[Zhouzhi County|Zhouzhi]],<ref name=\":19\"/> [[Xi'an]]\n|County\n|Shaanxi\n|2020-02-02\n|\n|562,768\n|2010\n|One person per household every day\n|-\n|[[Huyi District|Huyi]],<ref name=\":19\" /> [[Xi'an]]\n|District\n|Shaanxi\n|2020-02-03\n|2020-02-09\n|556,377\n|2010\n|One person per household every day\n|-\n|[[Bengbu]]<ref name=\"AutoDW-91\"/>\n|City\n|Anhui\n|2020-02-03\n|\n|3,164,467\n|2010\n|\n|-\n|[[Huaibei]]<ref name=\"AutoDW-92\"/>\n|City\n|Anhui\n|2020-02-03\n|\n|2,114,276\n|2010\n|\n|-\n|[[Bincheng District|Bincheng]],<ref name=\"auto6\" /><br />[[Binzhou]]\n|District\n|Shandong\n|2020-02-03\n|2020-02-09\n|682,717\n|2010\n|\n|-\n|[[Taizhou, Zhejiang|Taizhou]]<ref name=\"AutoDW-93\"/>\n|City\n|Zhejiang\n|2020-02-03\n|\n|5,968,838\n|2010\n|\n|-\n|[[Hangzhou]]<ref name=\"AutoDW-94\"/>\n|City\n|Zhejiang\n|2020-02-04\n|\n|9,806,000\n|2017\n|\n|-\n|[[Ezhou]]<ref name=\"AutoDW-95\"/>\n|City\n|Hubei\n|2020-02-04\n|\n|1,048,668\n|2010\n|\n|-\n|[[Fuzhou]]<ref name=\"AutoDW-96\"/>\n|City\n|Fujian\n|2020-02-04\n|\n|7,660,000\n|2017\n|\n|-\n|[[Xuzhou]